column5: Barack Obama is the president of the United States. Obama was formerly a U.S. senator from Illinois. He was born in 1961 in Hawaii, where his parents met as students at the University of Hawaii. Obama's father is from Kenya and his mother is from Kansas. He graduated from Columbia University and received his law degree from Harvard Law School. Obama previously served in the Illinois state Senate and was an instructor at the University of Chicago Law School. He and his wife, Michelle, have two daughters, Malia and Sasha.

Joe Biden is the vice president of the United States. He was born in Scranton, Pa., but now lives in Wilmington, Del. He represented Delaware in the U.S. Senate from 1973 to 2009. He made a brief run for president in 1988 and again in 2007. He was announced Aug. 23, 2008, as Sen. Barack Obama's vice presidential nominee.
John Boehner of Ohio is the Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives. He was formerly the Republican minority leader from 2007-2011, and was the majority leader briefly prior to that.
Mitch McConnell is a U.S. Senator from Kentucky and the Republican majority leader in the U.S. Senate.
Rep. Nancy Pelosi is the minority leader of the U.S. House. Formerly the speaker of the House from 2007-11, Pelosi has been the House Democratic leader since January of 2003.
Harry Reid is a U.S. senator from Nevada and the Democratic minority leader in the U.S. Senate.

The 13th District GOP slate includes state Sen. Joe Kyrillos and Assembly members Declan O'Scanlon and Amy Handlin. The trio won their primary contests Tuesday, June 4 and will be on the November 2013 ballot.
The New Jersey State AFL-CIO represents union members and their families through legislative and political initiatives, and organizing members.

Greg Abbott won election as governor of Texas in November 2014, carrying 59 percent of the vote. Abbott, a former member of the Texas Supreme Court, served three terms as the state's attorney general before being succeeded by Ken Paxton in early 2015.

Chris Abele is Milwaukee County Executive, a position he won in an April 2011 special election to finish out the final year of the term of Scott Walker, who was elected governor in November 2010. The election was the first attempt at political office for Abele, a Milwaukee philanthropist and business owner.

	The office is nonpartisan, but Abele has indicated he is a Democrat.
A third-party group attacking St. Petersburg state Rep. Jim Frishe.

Steve Acenbrak first joined the City of Roswell as its Deputy Transportation Director in 2001. He has more than 28 years of engineering and management experience, according to the city's website. Acenbrak served as Roswell’s Transportation Director from 2002 – 2006. He returned on October 20, 2008, after working two years as the Director of Civil Engineering for Pond & Company.
Acevedo, a former California highway trooper, was appointed Austin's chief of police in July 2007.
An anonymous activist is a person or group not identified.
Sam Adams is the mayor of Portland. Before that he was a city commissioner and , for 11 years, was chief of staff to then-Mayor Vera Katz.
Sandy Adams is a Republican member of Congress. In 2012, she is running to represent District 7.

Cathie Adams served as the Republican Party of Texas chair from October 2009 to June 2010. She was previously elected to the Republican National Committee and has been a delegate to every state and senatorial district Republican convention since 1988. Before becoming chair, she helmed the Texas Eagle Forum. She lives in Dallas.
Janet Adkins lives in Fernandina Beach and was elected as a Republican to the state Legislature in 2008.
Attorney Steve Adler won election as mayor of Austin in December 2014, drawing 67 percent of the vote in a December 2014 runoff. He was sworn in on Jan. 6, 2015.
Yolanda Adrean is an Atlanta city councilwoman who represents portions of north Atlanta that include Buckhead.
Citizens Against Rail Taxes, a political action committee, opposes the rail proposition on the City of Austin ballot in November 2014.
Marisha Agana is a Republican candidate for Congress from Ohio's newly drawn 13th Congressional District. She is a pediatrician from suburban Warren, Ohio.
Larry Ahern is a member of the Florida House of Representatives representing District 51. He was first elected in 2010.
Former American Idol runner-up Clay Aiken is running for U.S. House in North Carolina's second congressional district.
Doug Ainge has taught at Banks High School since 1979. He is brother to Danny Ainge, former pro basketball player.

Edith H. Ajello has been a Rhode Island state representative since November 1992. A Democrat, she chairs the House Committee on Judiciary and is a member of the House Oversight Committee. She lives in Providence and works in oriental rug restoration and sales at V. George Rustigian Rugs.
CEO of Qatar Airways
David Alameel, a dentist-turned-investor, was the Democratic U.S. Senate nominee in Texas in 2014.
Sal Albanese is a Democratic candidate for mayor of New York City in 2013. A former New York City council member, Albanese later served as managing director of Mesirow Financial.
Luis Alejo, Democratic state lawmaker from Salinas
Sen. J.D. Alexander is a Republican from Lake Wales. He was first elected to the Florida Senate in 2002.
Dennis L. Algiere is a Republican state senator from Westerly, R.I. He is a senior vice president at Washington Trust Company, in Westerly.
Rick W. Allen is running as a Republican for the U.S. House seat currently held by Democrat John Barrow. He unsuccessfully ran for the seat in 2012. Allen owns an Augusta-based construction business.
Diane Allen is a Republican state senator representing parts of Burlington County.
George Allen was a U.S. senator from 2001-2007. He was governor of Virginia from 1994-1998.
A former candidate for governor and state treasurer, Allen Alley is the founder of Pixelworks, where he was CEO for 10 years.

The Alliance for America’s Future is a Virginia-based group that supports Republican candidates and conservative causes. Its principals include Barry Bennett, a former top aide to Rep. Jean Schmidt, a Republican from southwest Ohio, and political consultant Mary Cheney, former Vice President Dick Cheney’s daughter.

Founded in 2001, the Alliance for Retired Americans says its mission is to "ensure social and economic justice and full civil rights for all citizens so that they may enjoy lives of dignity, personal and family fulfillment and security."

Ernest Almonte served as Rhode Island's Auditor General from 1994 to 2010. He has served as president of the Rhode Island Society of Certified Public Accountants and the National Association of State Auditors. He is founder of the Almonte Group, an accounting firm. He is married with five sons. In 2014 he made an unsuccessful run for Rhode Island General Treasurer as an independent.
Roberto Alonzo of Dallas was initially elected to the Texas House in 1992. He lost his re-election in 1996, but returned to the House after winning afresh in 2004.
Thad Altman was elected to the state Senate in 2008 from Senate District 24. Previously he served in the state House.
Carol Alvarado represents Houston in the Texas House of Representatives. Before being elected, she served on the Houston City Council from 2002-2008 and as Mayor Pro Tem from 2004-2008.
Representative Justin Amash represents Michigan’s Third District. He was elected to his first term in 2010.
attorney and Libertarian candidate for House District 21
AHIP is a trade group representing the health insurance industry.
The American Beverage Association is an trade group that represents hundreds of beverage producers, distributors, franchise companies and support industries for non-alcoholic drinks.

American Bird Conservancy is a nonprofit organization whose mission is to conserve native birds and their habitats throughout the Americas. The group opposes a feral cat bill proposed in the 2013 Florida Legislature.

The American Civil Liberties Union bills itself as "the nation’s premier defender of the rights enshrined in the U.S. Constitution," defending "individual freedoms including speech and religion, a woman’s right to choose, the right to due process, citizens’ rights to privacy and much more . . . even when the cause is unpopular, and sometimes when nobody else will."
The American Civil Liberties Union of Florida advocates for "individual rights and personal freedoms guaranteed by the Constitution and the Bill of Rights."

The American LeadHERship PAC is a political action committee that describes itself as "an organization dedicated to increasing the ranks of progressive women in governors' seats across the country." During the 2014 election, the only candidate featured on its website was Gina Raimondo, a Democrat who was ultimately elected Rhode Island governor.
American Principles in Action is a conservative group "dedicated to preserving and propagating the fundamental principles on which our country was founded."
Americans Against Food Taxes is a coalition of food, beverage and grocery companies that oppose taxes on sodas and other snacks.
Americans United for Life is an anti-abortion law firm and advocacy group based in Washington, D.C.
Americans for Prosperity Florida is the Florida affiliate of a free-market group that fights "big government."

Americans for Safe Access (ASA) works toward "ensuring safe and legal access to cannabis (marijuana) for therapeutic uses and research," according to its website. It was founded in 2002 and has offices in California and Washington D.C.
Elizabeth Ames Jones resigned from the Texas Railroad Commission to run for a Texas Senate seat in 2012. She formerly served in the Texas House.
State Rep. Ron Amstutz represents the 3rd House District, which includes all of Wayne County, Ohio. He has 30 years of service in both the Ohio Senate and the Ohio House.
Brian Anderson is a homeless advocate who testified before the Florida Legislature.
Shirley Anderson is a candidate for the Hernando County Supervisor of Elections in 2012.
Rob Andrews is a Democratic congressman representing New Jersey's 1st district, which includes parts of Camden, Gloucester and Burlington counties.

Joseph Andriole worked as a firefighter in Central Falls for 22 years. After retiring in 2009, he began working full-time as vice president of the Rhode Island State Association of Firefighters. He previously worked part-time as the association’s business agent.
Kathleen Angelucci, a Republican, is district 4 representative on the Cobb County school board.
Sharron Angle is a former member of the Nevada Assembly who unsuccessfully tried to unseat Harry Reid in 2010 as the Republican nominee for his U.S. Senate seat.
Ted Ankrum is a retired Navy captain who ran for the U.S. House in 2010.
Frank R. Annunziato is executive director of the University of Rhode Island chapter of the American Association of University Professors, a labor union and advocacy group.
This website pranked Republican Carly Fiorina around the time she announced her presidential bid in 2015.

Nickie J. Antonio is a state representative for the 13th Ohio House District. She was first elected to the statehouse in 2010. She represents residents from the city of Lakewood and parts of the West Side of Cleveland.

Julaine Appling is executive director of Wisconsin Family Action, a Madison, Wis., based 501(c)(4) organization formed in 2006, according to its website, "in order to do statewide education, grassroots activities, election-related work as the law provides and advocacy in the state legislature on cultural and legislative issues that either threaten or strengthen Wisconsin's most valuable natural resource—her traditional families." The group says its mission is to advance Judeo-Christian principles and values in Wisconsin by strengthening and preserving marriage, family, life and liberty.

Steve Archambault was a candidate for attorney general in 2010. A 2000 graduate of the Roger Williams School of Law, he is a former police officer in Jamestown, Lincoln town prosecutor, a lawyer, and a member of the Smithfield Town Council.
Natalyn Mosby Archibong is the District 5 representative on the Atlanta City Council. She was first elected to office in 2001.
Diego Arene-Morley, of Washington, D.C., is the president of Brown University Students for Sensible Drug Policy. He is a junior majoring in public policy.

Ward Armstrong, D-Henry County,  was a  a member of the Virginia House of Delegates from 1992 to 2012, serving the final five years as minority leader. He served on the Courts of Justice, Finance, and Rules committees. In 2011, House Republicans merged Armstrong's district with that of another incumbent, Republican Charles Poindexter. Armstrong was defeated by Poindexter that fall.

,

Dave Aronberg is a former state senator from Palm Beach County who campaigned to be Florida Attorney General and was defeated in the Democratic Primary on Aug. 24, 2010. He was elected Palm Beach State Attorney in 2012.
Larry Ashley was elected Okaloosa Sheriff in 2010. He began his law enforcement career at the Okaloosa County Sheriff’s Office in 1990 in the Uniformed Patrol Division.
Reza Aslan is a scholar of religions and author of several books, including Zealot: The Life and Times of Jesus of Nazareth. He teaches at the University of California, Riverside.
Associated Industries of Florida is a lobbying group focused on business issues.

The Association of Mature American Citizens was founded in 2007. Its founder, a retired insurance agency owner named Dan Weber, said he created it to counter what he saw as the political bias of the American Association of Retired Persons. Besides acting as a self-proclaimed conservative advocacy group, the organization offers discounts to members from cooperating businesses.

The Texas Association of School Boards, an advocacy and education group, says its membership includes every Texas school district, 20 regional education service centers, 50 community colleges, 38 tax appraisal districts and others. The group says its mission is to promote educational excellence for Texas schoolchildren.
Rob Astorino is a Republican who is the county executive of Westchester County, N.Y., just north of New York City. He is running against Democratic Gov. Andrew Cuomo.
Jeff Atwater, a former state Senator from North Palm Beach, was elected Florida Chief Financial Officer on Nov. 2, 2010 and re-elected Nov. 4, 2014.
James Aubin, of North Smithfield, is a member of Common Sense Citizen, a group he formed to fight for legalization of marijuana in Rhode Island.
Richard August, aka Sigmund Sauer, is a co-host on WHJJ's weekly radio show “Lock, Stock and Daria,” which discusses firearms-related issues.
Loranne Ausley, a former member of the Florida House of Representatives, campaigned to be Florida Chief Financial Officer and was defeated on Nov. 2, 2010.
Austin, the capital of Texas, is a city in Central Texas.
John Axford is a relief pitcher for the Milwaukee Brewers.
Carla Axtman is a writer for Blue Oregon, a left-leaning political blog.
Jimmie Don Aycock is a Texas House member from Killeen.

Kelly Ayotte is a U.S. Senator representing New Hampshire as a Republican. She was the first woman to serve as her state's attorney general. Appointed to that position in 2004 by a Republican governor, she was twice reappointed by a Democratic governor.
Dino Baccari lists himself as "founder and believer" of White Horse Vapor, which makes e-cigarettes.

Michele Bachmann, first elected to the U.S. Congress in 2006, represents the 6th Congressional District of Minnesota. She was reelected in 2008. Previously, she served in the Minnesota State Senate. Prior to that, she spent five years as a federal tax litigation attorney. Bachmann and her husband, Marcus, who have five children and have opened their home to 23 foster children, live in Stillwater, Minn., and own a mental health care practice.

Rep. Spencer Bachus has represented Alabama’s 6th district in the U.S. House since 1993. He became chairman of the Financial Services Committee following the midterm elections of 2010 after having served as the ranking member of that committee for four years prior.

Back to Basics is a political action committee that aims to "shed light on who are politicians are working for — themselves and their pals instead of hardworking Texas families," according to the group's website.

Charlie Baird, who was on the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals for nearly a decade, later served as a Travis County state district judge. He founded the criminal law section of an Austin law firm, according to the biography posted by his 2012 campaign for Travis County district attorney.
Thurbert Baker is Georgia Attorney General. He is a Democratic candidate for governor.
Lisa Baldelli-Hunt was a state representative from District 49 before being elected mayor of Woonsocket.

Tammy Baldwin was elected to the U.S. Senate on Nov. 6, 2012. She represented Wisconsin’s Second Congressional District from January 1999 to January 2013. She served as a member of the Wisconsin Assembly from January 1993 to January 1999. She was a Dane County supervisor from 1986 to 1994 and briefly served on the Madison Common Council, filling a vacancy, in 1986.
Adan Ballesteros initially won election as constable in 2008.
Ban the Box RI is a group that supports legislation prohibiting employers from including questions about criminal records on job applications.
Delta Spokesman.

Justin Barasky is the national press secretary for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, a Washington D.C.-based organization dedicated to maintaining a Democratic majority in the U.S. Senate.
Rev. William Barber is the president of the North Carolina NAACP.
Robert Barber is a retired captain with the Cranston Police Department.
Rick Barber was a tea party-affiliated candidate who lost the Republican nomination to represent Alabama’s 2nd congressional district.
Republican Governor of Mississippi, chairman of the Republican Governors Association and a former lobbyist.

Peter Barca, a Kenosha native and Democrat, has served two stints in the state Assembly. He was first elected in 1984 before resigning after winning a U.S. House seat in 1993. He served one term in Congress, losing re-election to Mark Neumann. Barca served in various governmental and private-sector posts before winning election to the Assembly in 2008. He was elected Minority Leader of the Assembly Democrats in 2011.
John Barge, a Republican, was elected by Georgia voters in 2010 as the state schools superintendent.

George L. Barker was first elected to the Virginia Senate in 2007.  Prior to his election, he had been active in a number of civic and community organizations.  

	Barker has two degrees from Harvard University, receiving undergraduate honors in Economics and Public Health and a master's in Health Policy and Management.  For three decades he worked for the Health Systems Agency of Northern Virginia.  He currently consults on health care issues.

	Barker and his wife reside in Clifton.  They have two grown children and were foster parents to 13 children.
Roy Barnes is the former governor of Georgia.

Former Congressman Bob Barr was the Libertarian Party's presidential nominee for 2008. Barr served in the U.S. House of Representatives from 1995 to 2003. Currently he runs Liberty Strategies LLC, a consulting firm with offices in Atlanta and Washington, D.C.
John Barrasso is a Republican senator from Wyoming.
Vincent Barrella is the mayor of Point Pleasant Beach.
Jimmy Barrett is a radio personality for WRVA-AM in Richmond, Va.

Tom Barrett has served as mayor of Milwaukee since 2004. He previously served in the U.S. House and the state Legislature. He lost bids for governor in 2002, 2010 and in the 2012 recall race against Gov. Scott Walker
U.S. Rep John Barrow represents Georgia's 12th Congressional District.
Maria Bartiromo is host of CNBC's On the Money with Maria Baritromo and a co-host of Closing Bell. She previously worked for CNN.

Joe Barton is a Republican congressman from Texas. He was formerly the chairman of the House Energy and Commerce committee and served as that committee’s ranking member while the Democrats were in the House majority.

David Barton of Aledo, vice chairman of the Republican Party of Texas from 1997 into 2006, is the founder and president of WallBuilders, which describes itself as a national pro-family  organization that presents America's forgotten history and heroes, with  an emphasis on our moral, religious and constitutional heritage.

Basic Rights Oregon describes itself as a 501(c)(4) organization, focusing primarily on policy and legislative changes "that contribute to a more fair and equal Oregon. 2007's historic domestic partnership and anti-discrimination legislation are prime examples of the work of Basic Rights Oregon."
Charlie Bass is a U.S. representative from New Hampshire.
William G. Batchelder is speaker of the Ohio House of Representatives. He represents the 69th House District, which encompasses most of Medina County.
Alan Bates is an Oregon state senator. He represents Senate District 3, which covers Medford.
Battleground Texas, a political action committee, was announced in early 2013 as an effort to help Democrats win statewide races in Texas.
Kurt Bauer is president of Wisconsin Manufacturers & Commerce, the state's largest business lobby.
Dennis Baxley is a state representative from Ocala, Fla.

Evan Bayh, a Democrat from Indiana, served two terms as governor (1989-1997) and two terms as U.S. senator (1999-2011), He is now a partner at McGuireWoods Consulting as well as a political commentator, a senior advisor at Apollo Global Management in New York, and a member of the advisory board of the Central Intelligence Agency.
Community activist, Common Core opponent, executive board member of Fayette County GOP
The Bear Education and Resource Group is a black bear advocacy group whose mission is to "teach residents how to live responsibly and peacefully with black bears."
Democrat Joyce Beatty was elected in 2012 to Ohio's 3rd District, a new congressional district in the Columbus area. She formerly was a state lawmaker.
Heather Beaven is a Democrat running for Congress in Florida's 7th Congressional District.
The city of Beaverton, seven miles west of Portland, is Oregon's sixth largest city with nearly 87,000 residents.
Xavier Becerra is a Democratic member of the U.S. House of Representatives from California.
Bob Beckel is a former Democratic consultant and current Fox News co-host of "The Five."

Paul Begala is an analyst for CNN and longtime Democratic strategist who came to national attention helping Bill Clinton win for president in 1992. He's a graduate of the University of Texas and UT School of Law.
U.S. Sen. Mark Begich is a Democrat from Alaska. He was elected in November 2008.
Director, Georgia C.A.R.E. (Campaign for Access, Reform and Education) - supporting legalization of marijuana
Rebecca Bell-Metereau is a professor at Texas State University in San Marcos, Texas. She ran for the Texas State Board of Education in 2010.
Mark Belling is a talk show host for WISN-AM (1130) in Milwaukee. His show airs weekdays from 3 p.m. to 6 p.m. He is an occasional fill-in host for Rush Limbaugh.
Lauren Benedict is chairwoman of Georgia's WIN List, a PAC dedicated to train and help Democratic women get elected to political office. Benedict is also a member of the Macon City Council.
Bennet is a U.S. Senator from Colorado.

Bill Bennett is former Education Secretary, drug czar and head of the National Endowment for the Humanities under Presidents Ronald Reagan and George H.W. Bush He is currently a political commentator for CNN.

Bob Bennett is chairman of the Ohio Republican Party. His current term began in 2012, and he plans to retire from the post May 31, 2013. He was an architect of the state party's modern-day successes, serving an earlier term as chairman from 1988 to 2009.
James Bennett is chairman of the  board of the Rhode Island Convention Center and director of Providence's Department of Economic Development.
Robert Bennett is a Republican senator from Utah.
Mike Bennett is a Republican state senator representing District 21. He was first elected to the Senate in 2002.
Holly Benson is a former secretary for the Agency for Health Care Administration. She campaigned to be Florida Attorney General and was defeated in the Republican primary on Aug. 24, 2010.
Ami Bera is a Democrat who represents a California district that includes Sacramento in the U.S. House of Representatives.
Phil Berger is a Republican from Eden and the president pro tempore of the North Carolina Senate.

Charlotte Bergmann is a former marketing professional who has been running as a Tea Party-style Republican for Tennessee's 9th Congressional District, which comprises Memphis and parts of the county's least-affluent suburban areas.

A graduate of Stanford University and Chicago University School of Law, Berke returned to his hometown of Chattanooga and in 2007 was elected to the state Senate. He is the vice-chairman of the Democratic caucus.
Mike Berlon is the chairman of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
Leo Berman is a state representative from Tyler.

Jack Berry is one of about a dozen candidates running for Richmond mayor in 2016. He recently resigned as executive director of Venture Richmond, an organization that promotes Richmond through economic development, marketing, festivals and events.

Berry worked as budget analyst and assistant city manager in Richmond and was county administrator in Hanover County. He joined Venture Richmond in 2006.

Carlos Beruff is a Bradenton developer running for U.S. Senate. His company, Medallion Homes, operates in Manatee and Sarasota counties. He has never held an elected office, but then-Gov. Charlie Crist in 2009 appointed him to the Sarasota-Bradenton Airport Authority, the Southwest Florida Water Management board and the State College of Florida board. Gov. Rick Scott reappointed him to all three positions and in 2015 picked Beruff to lead his hospital commission.
lawyer and member of state senate
46-yearold investment manager.

Donald S. Beyer Jr. is the Democratic nominee for 8th District congressional seat Democrat in Northern Virginia. The seat has been occupied since 1992 by Democrat Jim Moran, who is not seeking reelection.

Beyer served two terms as Virginia's lieutenant governor from 1990 to 1998. He ran for governor in 1997 and lost to Republican Jim Gilmore. From 2009 to 2013, he was ambassador to Switzerland and Liechtenstein.  

Beyer and his younger brother, Michael, are the owners of nine car dealerships in Northern Virginia.

Beyer was born in 1950 in Trieste, Italy, the son of a U.S. Army officer. He was raised in Washington, D.C. and graduated from Williams College, magna cum laude, with a degree in economics.
Big Gamble NJ is a joint campaign started by the Communications Workers of America and the Asian American Retailers Association that opposes efforts to privatize the state lottery.
BikePortland.org is an independent, daily news source that covers the Portland bike scene, run by Jonathan Maus.
Rep. Gus Bilirakis is a Republican Congressman from Florida. He represents the 9th Congressional District, an area north of Tampa Bay.
Jeremy Bird, a founding partner of 270 Strategies, also is a senior consultant to Battleground Texas, a group hel helped form that's focused on turning Texas pro-Democratic.

Brian Birdwell won a special election in June 2010 to fill the Texas Senate seat vacated by Kip Averitt, R-Waco. He was sworn in as senator in late July. Retired from the U.S. Army, Birdwell launched Face The Fire Ministries, a non-profit organization that supports critical burn survivors and wounded servicemen and women and their families, according to his campaign website. Severely burned in the Sept. 11, 2001 attack on the Pentagon, Birdwell says he subsequently underwent 39 operations.
JoAnn Birrell, a Republican, is the District 3 representative on the Cobb County Commission.
Democrat Sanford Bishop represents Georgia's 2nd Congressional District
Barney Bishop is the president and CEO of Associated Industries of Florida, a pro-business group supporting more offshore oil drilling.
Ben Bius is a real estate investor from Huntsville. He lost the 2010 Republican primary to Texas Sen. Steve Ogden.

The former Tennessee state legislator was elected to Congress in the Republican wave of 2010. She lives in a suburb of Nashville, Gallatin, and represents the state's 6th Congressional District, which encompasses areas north, east and south of Nashville.

	She has worked as both an emergency-room nurse and long-term care nurse, is married to a doctor and advocates for what she calls "market based" health-care reform.
Elected Georgia's first GOP farm chief in 2010
Marsha Blackburn, a native of Laurel, Miss., was first elected to represent Tennessee’s 7th Congressional District in 2002.
Lisa Blais is on the board of directors of Ocean State Tea Party in Action.
Christopher Blazejewski, a lawyer and Providence resident, has been a state representative since 2011.
Lisa Bloom is a TV legal analyst and author of Swagger: 10 Urgent Rules for Raising Boys in an Era of Failing Schools, Mass Joblessness, and Thug Culture.
Michael Bloomberg is the former mayor of New York City.
The blog BlueOregon describes itself as "the water cooler around which Oregon progressives will gather."

Earl Blumenauer is the Democratic representative for Oregon's 3rd Congressional District. He was elected to the US House of Representatives in 1996. He started in politics in the Oregon Legislature in 1972, where he served three terms. In 1978, he was elected to the Multnomah County Board of Commissioners, where he served for eight years before being elected to the Portland City Council in 1986. He was a city commissioner for 10 years.
Richard Blumenthal has been a United States Senator from Connecticut since Jan. 5, 2011. A Democrat, he formerly served as the state's attorney general.
Roy Blunt is the junior U.S. senator from Missouri. He was formerly a U.S. representative from Missouri’s 7th district, and served for six years as the Republican whip in that chamber.
John Boccieri is former member of Congress. A Democrat, he represented Ohio's 16th Congressional District.
State Rep. Ellyn Bogdanoff of Fort Lauderdale is running for the Florida Senate.
Jack Bogdanski is a local blogger.
State Rep. Dwayne Bohac is a Republican from Houston.

Jim Bohl has served as an alderman on the Milwaukee Common Council since April 2000. Before being elected, he worked as a high school teacher and as an aide to Milwaukee Mayor Tom Barrett, when Barrett served as a Democratic member of Congress.
Since 1997, David Boies has been the chairman of the law firm Boies, Schiller & Flexner LLP. He is among attorneys to challenge state restrictions on same-sex marriage.
Kitty Boitnott was president of the Virginia Education Association, an organization of about 60,000 public school teachers, from 2008 to 2012..
Valinda Bolton was first elected to represent district 27 in the Texas House of Representatives in 2006. She lost the 2010 general election to Paul Workman.
Suzanne Bonamici is a member of the Oregon Senate. She is also the Democratic nominee to represent the state's 1st congressional district.
Pam Bondi, a former Hillsborough County prosecutor, was elected Floriday Attorney General on Nov. 2, 2010 and re-elected Nov. 4, 2014.
Barry Bone won election as mayor of Rollingwood in 2012.

Ron Book is one of the most powerful lobbyists in Florida and lobbies the state Legislature. Based in Aventura in South Florida,  Book represents numerous businesses, associations and local governments including Broward and Miami-Dade counties. He has represented the Miami Dolphins since 1982.
New Jersey Democrat Cory Booker, the former mayor of Newark, N.J., was elected to the U.S. Senate in 2013.
John Boozman represents the 3rd district of Arkansas in the U.S. House of Representatives
Dan Boren is a Democrat who represents a district in Oklahoma in the U.S. House of Representatives.
Andy Borowitz, a comedian, writes for The New Yorker magazine. As of June 2015, he had over 500,000 followers on Twitter.
Jonathan Boucher is the executive director of the Rhode Island Democratic Party.
Rick Boucher, a Democrat, served 14th terms as the U.S. Representative from Virginia's 9th District. He lost his re-election bid in 2010 to Republican Morgan Griffith..
Dr. Charles Boustany is a heart surgeon and a Republican congressman from Louisiana.
Rob Bovett is district attorney of Lincoln County, Oregon.
David Bowen is a Democratic member of the Wisconsin Assembly, representing a district in Milwaukee. he is a former member of the Milwaukee County Board of supervisors.
Barbara Boxer is California's junior senator.
Kevin Boyce, a Democrat, is Ohio's state treasurer.
Allen Boyd is a former congressman from Monticello representing Florida's 2nd Congressional District in North Florida. He was defeated in a re-election campaign on Nov. 2, 2010.
Barth Bracy is executive director of Rhode Island Right to Life.

Bill Bradbury is a former Oregon secretary of state and an Oregon Democratic Party rock star. He ushered in the era of  vote-by-mail after Oregonians approved a citizen ballot measure to switch to mail in voting in 1998.
John Bradley, the district attorney in Williamson County since 2001, lost his 2012 bid for the Republican nomination.
Brady represents a Houston-area U.S. House district.
Bill Brady is a member of the Illinois state Senate. He was narrowly defeated as the Republican challenger to Governor Pat Quinn in the 2010 election.
a Democratic member of the U.S. House of Representatives representing Iowa
Jon Bramnick is a Republican state assemblyman representing parts of Morris, Somerset and Union counties. Bramnick also serves as the Assembly Republican Leader.
Dan Branch entered the Texas House in 2003. In 2014, he ran unsuccessfully for the Republican nomination for attorney general, giving up his shot at re-election to the House.

Jeff Brandes, 34, is director of real estate at Tibbetts Holdings LLC, his family's business. He is a Republican running Nov. 2, 2010, for the Florida House in District 52 against state Rep. Bill Heller, D-St. Petersburg.

Dave Brat, chairman of the business and economics department at Randolph-Macon College, is opposing House Majority Leader Eric Cantor in a 2014 Republican primary for the 7th Congressional District seat.

Brat, a midwestern native, has obtained a Masters in Divinity from Princeton Theological Seminary and a Ph.D. in economics from American University. He began teaching at Randolph-Macon in 1996.

Brat served two Governors on the Joint Advisory Board of Economists. He was president of the Virginia Association of Economists.

A longtime Democratic political consultant and campaign manager for Al Gore’s 2000 presidential campaign. Currently a political commentator for CNN and frequent commentator on ABC's This Week with George Stephanopoulos.

Brittany Brees, whose husband is New Orleans Saints quarterback Drew Brees, who played high school ball for Westlake High School, helped make a PSA urging attention to child abuse and prevention in November 2015.
Ian Bremmer is president and founder of the Eurasia Group, an international research and consulting firm, as well as a professor at New York University.
Jan Brewer, a Republican, is the former governor of Arizona.
Jim Bridenstine is a Republican representing an Oklahoma district in the House of Representatives.
Jon Brien served as a state representative from Woonsocket for six years, from 2007 through 2012.

Mark Brodeur is director of tourism at the Rhode Island Economic Development Corporation. A graduate of Johnson & Wales University in Providence, he has worked in the tourism and hospitality industry for 25 years.
Jason Brodeur is a member of the Florida House of Representatives serving District 33. He was first elected in 2010.

Frank T. Brogan is Chancellor of the State University System of Florida. Brogan began his career as a classroom teacher and later served as Florida's Commissioner of Education. He was elected Lieutenant Governor in 1998 and the Republican was re-elected in 2002. A year later, Brogan was selected to be president of Florida Atlantic University — a position he held until 2009, when the Board of Governors of the State University System unanimously chose him to serve as Chancellor of Florida's public universities.
State Representative Tyrone Brooks, D-Atlanta, represents Georgia's 55th House District.
Jace Brooks, a Republican, is District 1 representative on the Gwinnett County Board of Commissioners. District 1 includes Suwanee, Sugar Hill, Duluth, and parts of the Collins Hill community.
U.S. House Rep. Paul Broun, a Republican, is from Athens. He represents Georgia's 10th congressional district.
The association represents 1,500 allopathic and osteopathic physicians of all specialties in Broward County, Florida.
The Broward County Police Benevolent Association is the union that represents police officers and deputies including the Hollywood police and the Broward Sheriff's Office.

The Broward Democratic Executive Committee consists of hundreds of activists elected by their neighborhood precincts to represent the party. The volunteers work to elect Democrats to local, state and national office.

The Broward Republican Executive Committee (BREC) is the main county GOP party group in Broward -- a county where registered Democrats outnumber Republicans two to one but the more than 250,000 GOP voters can sway statewide races. The group consists of hundreds of activists who share the goal of electing Republicans to local, state and national office.

Scott Brown was elected a Republican U.S. senator from Massachusetts in 2010. He lost re-election in 2012 and subsequently became a political commentator for Fox News. In March 2014, Brown announced that he was considering entering the U.S. Senate race in New Hampshire.
Jerry Brown is the governor of California. A Democrat, he earlier served as governor of California from 1975 to 1983.

Andy Brown, initially elected chairman of the Travis County Democrats in 2008, served in that role until he ran for Travis County judge in 2014. He was previously executive director of the 21st Century Democrats in Texas.
Joe Brown is the founder, president, and CEO of Empire Incorporated, a chemical supply and janitorial service company. He was first elected to the Memphis City Council in 1998.
Thomas Brown, a Democrat, is the sheriff of DeKalb County, Georgia.
Kate Brown is Oregon's governor. She previously served as secretary of state.
Steven Brown is the executive director of the Rhode Island affiliate of the American Civil Liberties Union, a post he has held for three decades.
Corrine Brown was elected to Congress from the Third District of Florida in 1992.
Steve Brown, a Republican, is a commissioner on the Fayette County Board of Commissioners.
Robert Brown, a Democrat from Macon, is a Georgia state senator.
Sherrod Brown is a Democratic U.S. Senator representing Ohio.
Ginny Brown-Waite is a former Republican congresswoman from Brooksville in Florida’s 5th Congressional District. She halted her re-election campaign in April 2010 citing health reasons.

Sam Brownback is a U.S. senator from Kansas, elected to that job in 1996. He previously served one term in the U.S. House and also was the state agriculture commissioner. He graduated from Kansas State University and earned a law degree from the University of Kansas. He was born in Garnett, Kan., in 1956. He and his wife, Mary, have five children. He withdrew from the presidential race on Oct. 19, 2007.
Kurt Browning is Florida's Secretary of State. He previously served as Pasco County supervisor of elections.

Scott Bruun is an Oregon state representative running for the 5th Congressional District seat.

	See his profile in The Oregonian's Your Government page.

Anthony Bucco is a Republican State Senator representing parts of Morris and Somerset counties. Prior to joining the Senate in 1998, Bucco served in the State Assembly for three years. Bucco has served as the Senate's Republican Budget Officer since 2009.

James Buchal, a Portland attorney, says he is running for Congress "because the federal government is out of control and threatening our freedom and prosperity." Buchal has an A.B. degree in physics from Harvard College, a J.D. from Yale Law School and an M.B.A. from Yale School of Management. He ran unsuccessfully for Oregon attorney general in 2012.
Vern Buchanan has represented Florida's 13th Congressional District since 2007.
Ken Buck was the 2010 Republican U.S. Senate nominee from Colorado, having unsuccessfully challenged Sen. Michael Bennet for his seat.
Bob Buckhorn is making his second run for mayor in Tampa's nonpartisan elections on March 1, 2011. He previously served on the City Council from 1995-2003.
Served 16 years in the Georgia House of Representatives and two years in the state Senate.
Steve Buckstein is senior policy analyst at the Cascade Policy Institute, a think tank that advocates for limited government and free-market policies.

Rep. Armond Budish, a Democrat from Beachwood, Ohio, formerly was speaker of the Ohio House of Representatives. Be became the minority leader in 2011 after Republicans regained control of the House in the 2010 elections.
Dr. Knute Buehler is a Bend orthopedic surgeon and Republican candidate for Oregon secretary of state.
Ann Marie Buerkle is a Republican U.S. representative from New York, having defeated Rep. Dan Maffei for his seat in the 2010 election.
Warren Buffett is an investor and philanthropist. He is the CEO of Berkshire Hathaway Inc., based in Omaha, Neb.

Building a Better Ohio is a political action committee promoting passage of Issue 2 in Ohio. Passage of the state issue would allow provisions of Senate Bill 5, a law overhauling collective bargaining rules for public workers in Ohio, to be implemented.
Barbara Buono is a Democratic state senator representing part of Middlesex County. Buono previously served in the State Assembly from 1994 to 2001.
The U.S. Census Bureau oversees the decennial government census and related research including the annual American Community Survey.
Burger King is an international fast-food restaurant.

Burgess, initially elected to Congress in 2002, founded and chairs the Congressional Health Care Caucus, which raises questions about the Democratic-steered overhaul of federal health laws that passed into law in the spring of 2010.

Josh Burgin, 34, of Plant City is making his first run for office in seeking the Republican nomination for an at-large seat on the Hillsborough County commission. Burgin previously served as a state legislative aide, a county commissioner's aide and taught American history and English in Russia.

Burke is a former Trek Bicycle executive and former Wisconsin Commerce Department secretary who announced on Oct. 7, 2013 that she would seek the Democratic nomination for governor in Wisconsin in the fall 2014 election against incument Republican Gov. Scott Walker. She lost to Walker on Nov. 4, 2014. She is a school board member in Madison, Wisconsin.
Lon Burnam represented District 90 (which covers parts of Fort Worth and Tarrant County) from 1997 through 2014. He lost his bid for re-election in the 2014 Democratic primary.
Phil Burress, president of Citizens for Community Values
George Prescott Bush, formerly a corporate lawyer, won election as Texas land commissioner in 2014.

Jeb Bush has suspended his campaign for president of the United States in 2016. He served two terms as the governor of Florida from 1999 to 2007. He is also the brother of former President George W. Bush and the son of former President George H.W. Bush.

George W. Bush served as the 43rd president of the United States. He was sworn into office on Jan. 20, 2001, re-elected on Nov. 2, 2004, and sworn in for a second term on Jan. 20, 2005. Prior to his presidency, President Bush served six years as the 46th governor of the state of Texas.
John Buss is the water resources manager for the city of Tallahassee.
buzzfeed.com

The Conservatives Acting Together PAC is listed with a Dallas address on the Federal Election Commission's website. A May 21, 2012, Texas Tribune news story said the PAC had spent $113,646 on ads supporting former Railroad Commission chair Michael Williams' bid for Congress.
Herman Cain is an author, columnist and talk radio host. Cain, a former pizza franchise CEO, ran for president as a Republican in 2012.
Florida District 79 representative (Lehigh Acres). First elected in 2010.
Kevin Cameron is Oregon's House Republican Leader. He represents District 19 in Salem.

The Campaign for Liberty describes itself as an organization that believes the U.S. Constitution is a "living document" that should be adhered to by lawmakers. The organization supports individual liberty and a "noninterventionist foreign policy."
Campaign for Primary Accountability is a Texas-based political action committee that is targeting incumbent members of Congress.
Campaign to Defend America is a left-leaning advocacy organization.

Donna Campbell, a New Braunfels physician, won election to represent Texas Senate District 25 in November 2012. In 2010, she was the Republican nominee for the U.S. House seat held by Democrat Lloyd Doggett of Austin.
Stacey Campfield represents District 7 -- part of Knox County -- in Tennessee's state Senate.
Steve Cannon is CEO of Mercedes-Benz USA. Previously, he was the company's marketing director.
Ben Cannon is Gov. John Kitzhaber's chief education adviser. He used to serve in the Oregon House of Represenatives, representing District 46.
Dean Cannon (R-Winter Park) is the Florida Legislature's 2010 House Speaker and a lawyer.
Tim Canova is running in the 2016 Democratic primary for a South Florida congressional seat held by Debbie Wasserman Schultz.
Francisco "Quico" Canseco, a businessman and banker, won election to the U.S. House in 2010, but lost his re-election bid in 2012.

Eric Cantor is a seventh-term congressman representing the Seventh District of Virginia. In December 2008, he was elected to serve as the Republican Whip. Two years later he was elected Majority Leader, a position he currently holds. Cantor previously sat on the House Ways and Means Committee, which has direct jurisdiction over taxes, trade, Social Security, Medicare, prescription drugs for seniors, health care and welfare reform.
Rhode Island state director of the International Brotherhood of Police Officers.
Shelley Moore Capito is a U.S. Representative from West Virginia and a Republican candidate for U.S. Senate.

Frank T. Caprio Jr. served as Rhode Island's general treasurer from 2007 through 2010. He ran an unsuccessful campaign for governor in 2010 and ran for treasurer again in 2014, losing in the Democratic primary. Prior to that, he served as a state senator from 1995-2006 and as a state representative from 1991 to 1994. He is married and has two children.
Donald Carcieri, a Republican, served as Rhode Island's governor from 2003 to 2010. He is a former CEO of Cookson America.
Sen. Ben Cardin is a Democrat from Maryland. He has served in the Senate since 2007.
Barbara Cargill is a science educator who served on the State Board of Education.

John Carlevale of West Greenwich, R.I., has run for several offices, most recently in an unsuccessful bid for secretary of state in 2014 as a Republican. A graduate of Mt. Pleasant High School and the University of Rhode Island, he received a graduate degree in child development and family relations. Carlevale spent 33 years in human services,  helped found the Rhode Island chapter of the Social Service Employees Union International, and taught at the Community College of Rhode Island for 31 years. He is co-founder of the State of the State public access television show, which advocates for better government.

According to her biographical information, Margaret Carlson has written a politics column for Bloomberg. She's a former White House correspondent for TIME and appeared on CNN's "Capital Gang" for 15 years.
Gretchen Carlson is a co-anchor of the Fox News Channel morning show Fox & Friends.
Russ Carnahan is a Democratic congressman from Missouri.
Jay Carney, the White House press secretary, was formerly employed by TIME magazine and CNN, according to a TIME biographical post.
Manages Roy Barnes campaign

James Carr is a Libertarian candidate for the 7th Congressional District in 2014. He lives in Louisa County and is manager of business operations systems at a community hospital in Charlottesville. He has a bachelors degree in finance from the College of William and Mary, Williamsburg. He has previously worked as a road manager for a rock band and as a financial analyst for a defense contractor.

Jennifer Carroll, a former Florida state representative from House District 13 in North Florida, was elected Florida lieutenant governor on Nov. 2, 2010, as Gov. Rick Scott's running mate. Carroll resigned from office on March 13, 2013.
Meria Joel Carstarphen, superintendent of the Austin Independent School District, was previously superintendent of the Saint Paul (Minn.) Public Schools.

Jason Carter was elected to the Georgia Senate in May 2010, representing portions of DeKalb County. He is an attorney at the business litigation firm of Bondurant, Mixson & Elmore, LLP. Carter is the grandson of former U.S. president and Georgia governor Jimmy Carter.
Stefani Carter is a Republican state representative from Dallas.
Carter, of Georgetown, was initially elected to the U.S. House in 2002. He is a former state district judge.
Liz Carter is a Republican running for Georgia's 4th Congressional District.

Jimmy Carter was elected president of the United States in 1976 and served one term. He won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2002. The native of Plains, Georgia was submarine commander, peanut farmer, state senator and Georgia governor.
Alberto Carvalho is the superintendent for Miami-Dade Public Schools, the nation's fourth-largest school district.
James Carville is a Democratic political consultant and political commentator.
Caroline Casagrande is a Republican assemblywoman from Freehold, NJ, representing District 11.
Bob Casey, a Democrat, is a U.S. Senator representing Pennsylvania.
Bill Cassidy, a Republican, represents a Louisiana disrict in the U.S. House of Representatives. He challenged incumbent Democratic Sen. Mary Landrieu in 2014.

Kathy Castor is a member of the U.S. House of Representatives for Florida’s 14th Congressional district, which includes Tampa and St. Petersburg and parts of Hillsborough, Pinellas and Manatee counties. She was first elected in 2006.
Initially elected to the Texas House in 2002, Joaquin Castro initially won election to the U.S. House in November 2012.
Julián Castro, initially elected mayor of San Antonio in May 2009, later resigned to serve as U.S. secretary of Housing & Urban Development. Castro keynoted the 2012 Democratic National Convention.
David Caton is executive director of the Florida Family Association, a group that fights against pornography and gay rights and addresses other social concerns.

Causa Oregon, based in Salem, is the Northwest's largest Latino civil and human rights organization. Its mission is to "foster a society that recognizes the contributions of immigrants and upholds the values of democracy, equality, and respect."

Chad Causey was the unsuccessful 2010 Democratic nominee in the race to succeed retiring Rep. Marion Berry, D-Ark. Previously, Causey spent 10 years working as an aide to Berry, including four years as his chief of staff.
James Cenerini is the legislative affairs/political action coordinator for Council 94, Rhode Island's largest state and municipal employees union.
Michael C. Cerullo is a psychotherapist in private practice in Exeter, R.I.

Lincoln Chafee is running for the Democratic nomination for president in 2016. He served one four-year term as Rhode Island's governor, beginning on Jan. 4, 2011. He was the first Independent to be elected to that office. He subsequently became a Democrat. As a Republican, he served as mayor of Warwick from 1992 to 1999, when he was appointed to the U.S. Senate following the death of his father, Sen. John H. Chafee. He was elected to a full Senate term in 2000. He is married with three children. In April 2015 he formed an exploratory committee to consider running for President.
Rep. Jason Chaffetz, R-Utah, a second-term congressman, is the national security chair for the House Oversight and Reform Committee.
Gordon Challstrom is a Medford businessman and Republican who is running for governor.
State House Rep. Jill Chambers has represented north DeKalb county near Buford Highway since 2003. She is best known for serving on the MARTA oversight committee known as MARTOC.
Saxby Chambliss, a Republican, is a United States senator from Georgia

Ronnie Chance, a Republican, is the majority leader of the Georgia Senate. Chance worked for U.S. Rep. Mac Collins and was U.S. Sen. Bob Dole’s executive director in Georgia when Dole ran for president in the mid-1990s. He represents portions of Fayette County.

ChangeAustin.org, a political action committee founded in 2008, describes itself as "dedicated to bringing ordinary voters of all persuasions and Austin’s local businesses to City Hall to demand fiscal restraint, open government, and that growth should pay for itself.   In essence, we are about building a cross-partisan movement for political reform."
Jeff Chapman is a GOP candidate for governor of Georgia
John Charles is the president and CEO of the Cascade Policy Institute, a free-market think tank.
Dominic Chavez ran for Place 5 on the Austin City Council in May 2012.

Linda Chavez-Thompson, who has West Texas roots, was the 2010 Democratic nominee for lieutenant governor of Texas. The long-time activist with the AFL-CIO also rose to prominence in the national Democratic Party.

Lawton "Bud" Chiles III is the son of former Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles. He campaigned as an independent candidate for Florida governor in 2010 and withdrew in September, between the primary and general elections, citing a lack of money.
Michael W. Chippendale, of Foster, is a Republican state representative for District 40 in Rhode Island.
Kari Chisholm blogs for and ehlps run Blue Oregon, a left-leaning political website.
Warren Chisum sought the Republican nomination for a seat on the Texas Railroad Commission in 2012.
Gary Chiusano is a Republican state Assemblyman representing parts of Morris, Sussex and Warren counties. Chiusano previously served as a Sussex County freeholder.
Joseph Chiusolo is a Republican candidate for Essex County Freeholder. Chiusolo currently serves as deputy mayor in Cedar Grove.

Upendra Chivukula is a Democratic state Assemblyman who represents parts of Middlesex and Somerset counties. He is challenging U.S. Rep. Leonard Lance for a seat in the House of Representatives this November.

Chris Chocola is president of the Club for Growth, an advocacy group for fiscally conservative, free-market policies. He is a former Republican member of the U.S. House representing a district in Indiana.
Choose: New Jersey is a nonprofit organization that markets the state to attract businesses and jobs to New Jersey.
Wayne Christian of Center, first elected to the Texas House of Representatives in 1996, lost his bid for the GOP nod in 2012.

The Christian Broadcasting Network was founded by Christian evangelist and Republican politician Pat Robertson. The network is headquartered in Virginia Beach, Virginia. Gordon Robertson, Pat's son, is CBN's CEO. The network produces The 700 Club and other syndicated shows.

Chris Christie is the governor of New Jersey and a candidate for the Republican nomination for president in 2016. As governor, Christie won office in 2010 and was re-elected in 2014. Prior to that, he was U.S. Attorney for the District of New Jersey from 2002 to 2008.

Steven Chu is the current Secretary of Energy in the administration of President Barack Obama. He is a Nobel Prize winner for physics, and was formerly the director of the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.

Vincent "Buddy" Cianci is a talk-radio host and ex-convict who spent more time serving as mayor of Providence (21 years from 1975 to 2002) than anyone in the city's history. He is the author of "Politics and Pasta: How I Prosecuted Mobsters, Rebuilt a Dying City, Advised a President, Dined with Sinatra, Spent Five Years in a Federally Funded Gated Community, and Lived to Tell the Tale." He was defeated in the 2014 mayoral election when he ran as an independent.

David Cicilline was elected to the 1st Congressional District in 2010. Before that, he was mayor of Providence, beginning in January, 2003. A Brown University graduate, he received his law degree from Georgetown University Law Center.

Originally from the northern New Hampshire town of Berlin, Jackie Cilley has been elected to both the N.H. House of Representatives and Senate. She is the owner of a marketing firm called Cilley Associates.

	Cilley currently lives in the town of Barrington and teaches at the University of New Hampshire Whittemore School of Business and Economics.

	She served in the House of Representatives from 2004-2006 and the Senate from 2006-2010. While serving at the in the Sanate she chaired  the Executive Departments and Administration committee and was co-chair of the Administrative Rules committee.
A former pro-audio engineer, attending college to seek a chemical engineering and material science.
Henry Cisneros, a former secretary of Housing & Urban Development and former mayor of San Antonio, is a businessman in the Alamo City.

Citizens United Political Victory Fund states that its mission is to support conservative candidates running for federal office who share a vision of reducing the size and scope of government, lowering taxes, cutting spending, promoting traditional family values and winning the war on terror. The group has opposed Sen. John McCain and Rudy Giuliani in the Republican Party primary. It is based in Washington, D.C.
Citizens for Fairness is an electioneering communications organization based in Melbourne. The group’s chairperson is listed as Carmella K. Falcone.
A political action committee opposing Florida's proposed Amendment 4.
Citizens for Transportation Mobility is an advocacy group that supports a 1 percent sales tax to pay for transportation projects in Georgia.

Citizens for a Progressive Wisconsin is an interest group that has been active in state-level politics. According to the Center for Responsive Politics, the liberal organization is primarily active in federal politics.

Citizens for a Strong America is based in Beaver Dam, Wis. It says it "promotes public policies that reduce tax burdens on families, increase public safety, and protect the rights of parents to make decisions about their children’s medical, psychological and educational well-being."
Citizens for the Republic is a conservative advocacy group headed by several veterans of the Reagan Administration.
Chris Clark is president of the Georgia Chamber of Commerce. The chamber is a private organization whose primary goal is to further the business interests of its membership.
Wesley Clark, a retired Army general, ran for president in 2004.

Democrat Fred Clark is a member of the Wisconsin state Assembly, representing the 42nd District near Baraboo. He was elected in 2008. He ran unsuccessfully against Republican state Sen. Luther Olsen in an August 2011 recall election.
Amy Clark Meachum is a judge for the 201st district court in Travis County.

David A. Clarke Jr. is a former Milwaukee Police Department patrol officer and commander who was appointed sheriff in March 2002 by Gov. Scott McCallum, a Republican. Clarke, running as a Democrat, has been re-elected to the post since November 2002.

	 

	\
Dave Claunch, a business owner, won his first term as mayor of West Lake Hills in 2008 after previously serving of its Wastewater Commission.

Mark Clayton won the Democratic primary for U.S. Senate, although Tennessee's Democratic Party has disavowed him as a Democrat and is asking its members to write in a candidate. He is a floor installer and former Army Reserve aircraft technician.
Clayton County government serves about 250,000 residents and has a five-member board of commissioners. The county seat is Jonesboro, located approximately 20 miles south of Atlanta.
The Clayton County school district, which has about 51,000 students, is located just south of Atlanta city limits.

Emanuel Cleaver II represents Missouri’s Fifth Congressional District and serves on the House Financial Services Committee. Previously he served for 12 years on the city council Kansas City, Mo., and elected mayor in 1991, the first African-American to hold the post.

Bill Clegg, a lawyer, is a former executive director for ethics and compliance at Textron. He is also a a former member of the board of directors of the Rhode Island Airport Corporation and a current member of the Rhode Island Commission on Judicial Tenure and Discipline. He ran for Congress in the 2nd District in 2010. Born in 1955, he graduated from the University of Rhode Island and the Syracuse University College of Law. Clegg was also a colonel in the U.S. Army Reserve and served in Iraq in 2004. He is married and the father of two.

State Rep. Brian Clem, D-Salem, is a fifth-generation Oregonian, who was born in Coos Bay and earned a college degree from Oregon State University in Corvallis. He and his wife, Carol, live in Salem with their daughter.
Jeff Clemens was elected to the state Senate in 2012 and previously served in the House of Representatives and as mayor of Lake Worth.
Bill Clinton was president of the United States from 1993 to 2001. He is married to former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, a possible 2016 presidential candidate.

Hillary Clinton is a candidate running for president of the United States in 2016. She served as U.S. Secretary of State during the first four years of the Obama administration. She is formerly a U.S. senator from New York, first elected in 2000. She was a candidate for president in 2008. She previously served as first lady when her husband, Bill Clinton, served two terms as president. She was born in Chicago in 1947, graduated from Wellesley College and earned a law degree at Yale Law School. She and her husband have one daughter.
George Clooney is an Oscar-winning actor and producer and activist.

James Clyburn is a Democratic member of the U.S. House of Representatives from South Carolina. He serves as Assistant Minority Leader -- the third-highest-ranking officer in the House Democratic leadership.
Kathleen Clyde was elected to the Ohio House of Representatives in November 2010. Her 68th District includes the majority of Portage County. She currently resides in Kent.

The Coalition for Fair Budget Priorities is an association of hotels, some located in downtown Portland, that opposes significant public subsidies going to a proposed hotel that would support the Oregon Convention Center. The group, on a website operated by another company, uses the acronym "OUCH" -- Our Unfortunate Convention Hotel.

The Coalition to Bring Jobs to R.I. is a 501(c)4 nonprofit created by officials at the Twin River slot parlor in Lincoln, R.I., to promote passage of a referendum that would allow table games at Twin River.

Dan Coats is the junior U.S. senator from Indiana, having been elected to succeed Sen. Evan Bayh in 2010. Coats previously served in the U.S. Senate from 1989 to 1999, and was Ambassador to Germany from 2001-2005 under President George W. Bush. He was also a prominent lobbyist and attorney in the private sector.
Gary Cobb, a longtime Travis County prosecutor, is a 2016 Democratic candidate for district attorney in the county.
Tom Coburn is a former U.S. Senator from Oklahoma and a physician.

Thad Cochran is the senior U.S. Senator representing Mississippi. He was elected to the Senate in 1978 after serving three terms in the U.S. House. A Republican, Cochran has served as chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
Richard Codey is a Democratic state senator representing parts of Essex and Morris counties. Codey served as New Jersey governor from November 2004 to January 2006.
Mike Coffman is a member of the U.S. House of Representatives, serving Colorado's 6th District.
Jeff Cogen is the chair of the Multnomah County Board of Commissioners. He founded the Portland Pretzel Co.
Milele Coggs is a member of the Milwaukee Common Council, representing the 6th District. She was elected to the seat in 2008.

Born May 24, 1949 in Memphis, Tenn.

	In the House since 2006, he's a regional whip for the Democrats. In August of 2008, he was instrumental in passing H.Res.194, a House resolution apologizing for the enslavement and racial segregation of African Americans. A fourth-generation Memphian, he got his start as a Shelby County Commissioner, and served in the Tennessee state Senate for 24 years, where he became known throughout the state as the “Father of the Tennessee Lottery.”
Democratic candidate for  the U.S. House in the South Carolina's 1st Congressional District; Stephen Colbert's sister
Sheryl Cole, Austin's mayor pro tempore, was an Austin City Council member through 2014 and ran for mayor that year.
Cole, a long-time Austin radio host, joined partners in launching KOKE FM in 2012. He hosts the station's weekday morning program from 6 a.m. to 10 a.m.
Rep. Tom Cole, R-Okla., was elected to Congress in 2002. He's a fifth-generation Oklahoman and one of the only Native Americans serving in Congress.

Coleman, initially elected to the Texas House in 1991, formerly chairs the Texas House Committee on County Affairs. Coleman says in his online biography that he's one of the authors of the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) in Texas, a program that makes health insurance available to more than 500,000 children from working families. He said he also helped simplify access to Medicaid for more than 600,000 Texas children, and worked to secure an increase of $161.5 million for at-risk child care services.

Tom Colicchio is the chef-owner of Craft Restaurants, which operates high-end restaurants in New York City, Las Vegas and elsewhere. He has also been the head judge on the Bravo reality cooking series “Top Chef.”
Collier worked for 20 years as a top executive at PriceWaterhouseCoopers, an international accounting firm, and then became chief financial officer of a Texas oil company.
Susan Collins is a Republican U.S. Senator representing Maine.
Gail Collins is a columnist with the New York Times. She previously served on the New York Times editorial board and as a columnist for the New York Daily News and Newsday.
A current member of Congress from Gainesville, GA.
Abel G. Collins, a Brown University graduate who lives in South Kingstown, R.I. is program manager for the Rhode Island chapter of the Sierra Club. He ran unsuccessfully for Congress in 2012.
Atlanta lawyer Loren Collins is author of the anti-birther blog Barackryphal. He ran in 2008 as a write-in candidate for U.S. Congress.

Mike Collins co-owns Collins Industries, a trucking company. His father, Mac, served six terms in the U.S. House of Representatives. Collins is running as a Republican for Georgia's 10th Congressional District.
Susan Combs was initially elected as state comptroller in 2006. Previously, she served as Texas agriculture commissioner and in the Texas House. She didn't seek re-election in 2014.
State Rep. Courtney Combs, a Republican, represents the 54th Ohio House District, which includes the cities of Hamilton, Fairfield, and Ross Township in Butler County.
Committee for Our Children's Future, a nonprofit group known as a 501(c)4, launched a television campaign in September 2011 to tout the reform efforts of Gov. Chris Christie.
The Committee to Protect Florida is headed by Rockie Pennington, a political consultant for Richard Corcoran, a Republican candidate for State House District 45.
Common Sense Now is a third-party group supporting Carlos Gimenez for Miami-Dade mayor.

Barbara Comstock, a Republican, has represented Fairfax County in Virginia's House of Delegates since 2010. In 2014, she announced her candidacy for the 10th District congressional seat being vacated by Republican Frank Wolf.

Comstock has held various staff positions on Capitol Hill. She has done opposition research for the Republican National Commiittee, was a staffer on George W. Bush's 2000 presidential campaign and consultant in Mitt Romney's 2012 presidential campaign. She is founding partner and co-principal of Corallo Comstock, a public relations and public policy firm.

Comstock was born in Springfield, Mass. She is a graduate of Middlebury College and Georgetown University Law Center.
Assemblyman Herb Conaway Jr. is a Democratic assemblyman representing parts of Burlington County.

Concerned Taxpayers of America has been running ads against Oregon's 4th District Rep. Peter DeFazio. It receives some of its money from the co-CEO of one of the world's largest hedge funds, Robert Mercer, who heads Renaissance Technologies of Setauket, N.Y., along with Peter Brown. The Washington Post reported the group's only other donor was Daniel G. Schuster Inc., a concrete firm in Owings Mills, Md., which gave two donations totaling $300,000
a conservative advocacy group
Oregon Rep. Jason Conger, R-Bend, represents House District 54.
Colleen Conley is founder and president of the Rhode Island Tea Party.
Kathleen Connell is a former secretary of state and one-time teacher who is the Rhode Island AARP’s senior state director.

Rep. Gerald E. “Gerry” Connolly is serving his third term in the U.S. House of Representatives from Virginia’s 11th District, which encompasses Fairfax County, Prince William County, and Fairfax City in Northern Virginia.

Connolly serves on the House Budget Committee, the House Committee on Foreign Affairs, and the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.

He is the Ranking Member of the Oversight and Government Reform Subcommittee on Government Operations, which covers many key issues relating to Northern Virginia’s workforce and economy.  Connolly also serves on the Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation, and Regulatory Affairs.  He is a senior member of the House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa and also serves on the Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific.  

Connolly is vice-chair of the New Democrat Coalition, co-chairing its Technology, Education and Entrepreneurship Task Force, chair of the Smart Contracting Caucus, co-chair of the Sustainable Energy and Environment Caucus, co-chair of the Congressional Caucus on U.S.-Turkey Relations and Turkish Americans, co-chair of the Congressional Caucus on Korea, and co-chair of the Congressional Caucus on Taiwan.  


 Connolly received a B.A. in Literature from Maryknoll College in Glen Ellyn, Illinois, and a M.A. in Public Administration from Harvard University in 1979.

After graduating from Harvard, Connolly spent 10 years on the staff of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, where he handled numerous issues including oversight of international economic issues and policies concerning the Middle East and the United Nations.

 Connolly also worked in the non-profit and private sectors for organizations and companies involved in international trade, regulatory matters, and research.
Kent Conrad is a Democratic Senator from North Dakota. He is the top Democrat on the Senate Budget Committee.
Jody Conradt coached the University of Texas women's basketball team for 31 years.

Charlie Crist, he stuck by the governor when he left the GOP to run as an independent for the U.S. Senate. Jim Gilmore, a Republican, was governor of Virginia from 1998-2002. He is seeking the 2016 GOP presidential nomination.

Gilmore was born in Richmond in 1949. His father was a grocery store meat cutter and his mother was a church secretary. Upon graduating from the University of Virginia in 1971, he enlisted in the Army for three years and served in the intelligence corps at NATO headquarters in Germany. 

Gilmore graduated from UVa's law school in 1977 and was elected Commonwealth's Attorney in Henrico County in 1987 and 1991 and, in 1993, was elected state attorney general.

Gilmore was elected governor in 1997, largely on a promise to repeal an unpopular local property tax on cars. He had succeeded in repealing 70 percent of the levy when the state entered in recession in 2001 and lawmakers refeused to continue phasing out the tax.

Gilmore ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in 2008, losing to Democrat Mark Warner. In 2007, he launched a brief campaign for the 2008 GOP presidential nomination. In 2009, he became president and CEO of the Free Congress Foundation, a conservative think tank.
