Alexander Snitker is running as a Libertarian candidate for the United States Senate in 2010 for the State of Florida. He spent eight years in the Marines and currently works as a AXSA Document Solutions, Inc.

A former National Security Agency contractor based in Hawaii, Edward Snowden released secret documents about NSA surveillance programs to journalists for the Washington Post and Guardian before fleeing to Hong Kong. He now lives in Russia, which granted him permission to stay there three years.

Pete Snyder is an entrepreneur and a Fox News contributor. He ran unsuccessfully for the Republican nomination for lieutenant governor in 2013.

He founded New Media Strategies, a social media marketing agency, in 1999. That company was acquired and Snyder worked as CEO through 2011, but continued as a senior adviser afterwards. In 2012, Snyder founded Disruptor Capital, a firm that invests in technology, marketing and public affairs start-ups in Virginia. 

Snyder graduated from the College of William and Mary, Williamsburg, and is a member of the board of visitors there.
Michael A. Solomon is a Democrat and president of the Providence City Council, representing Ward 5.
Suzanne Somers is an actress best known for her role in the 1970s sitcom "Three's Company."
Susan Sosnowski has been a state senator since 1997 and is chairwoman of the Senate Committee on Environment and Agriculture.

Steve Southerland, a funeral home owner in the Florida Panhandle, was elected to the U.S. House representing Congressional District 2 on Nov. 2, 2010. He lost re-election to Democrat Gwen Graham on Nov. 4, 2014.

Zack Space, a Democrat, is a former representative from Ohio's 18th Congressional District, which stretches across all or part of 15 counties in southeast Ohio. He was defeated in the 2010 election by Republican Bob Gibbs.

Arlen Specter is a former U.S. senator from Pennsylvania. He was initially elected to the Senate in 1980 as a Republican and was elected another four times on the Republican banner, even serving for a time as chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, before switching parties in 2009 to become a Democrat. He was denied the Democratic U.S. Senate nomination in 2010, losing in the primary to Rep. Joe Sestak, and retired in 2011.
Rep. Jackie Speier, D–Calif., represents the state's 14th District, which includes most of San Mateo County and part of San Francisco.

Bill Spelman, won election to his second stint on the Austin City Council in 2009, having previously served from 1997 to 2000. He is a professor at the University of Texas Lyndon B. Johnson School of Public Affairs. He left the council on the change to a single-member district system in 2015.
Steve Spinnett is president of Steve's Imports, a car service and repair shop founded in 1975.
Mary Squires, a former state senator, is running for state Insurance Commissioner.
Debbie Stabenow is a Democratic Senator representing Michigan.

Bob Stacey was executive director of 1000 Friends of Oregon until 2009. He also has worked as chief of staff for Rep. Earl Blumenauer and for the Ball Janik law firm. He also has worked for TriMet and for then-Gov. Barbara Roberts as a senior policy adviser. He was elected to the Metro Council in May 2012.
Rep. Paul "Skip" Stam is a Republican and the House Speaker pro tem.
Stand For Children is a special-interest group pushing child and education issues.

Stanford is a political consultant and a syndicated columnist who writes for the Austin American-Statesman, MSNBC and the Huffington Post. He co-wrote the 2011 book "Adios Mofo: Why Rick Perry Will Make America Miss George W. Bush."

Staples was first elected agriculture commissioner of Texas in 2006 after previously serving in the Texas Senate and House. He unsuccessfully sought the 2014 Republican nomination for lieutenant governor, afterward resigning for another job.
Republican member of the Florida State Senate from the 15th District, which includes parts of Orange, Osceola, and Polk Counties, since 2012. Previously elected to House in 2008. Lives in Lakeland.

Bruce Starr is a state senator in the Oregon Legislature. He was elected to the House in 2002 and re-elected in 2006 before running for the Senate. He owned a construction business, has worked for the Portland Business Alliance and now runs a business,  Cutting Edge NW, advising companies on public affairs strategies. He also previously served on the Hillsboro City Council.
Cecil Staton, a Republican from Macon, is the majority whip in the Georgia Senate.
Cliff Stearns is a Republican from Ocala serving in the U.S. House of Representatives representing Congressional District 6.
Michael Steele is the chairman of the Republican National Committee. He was formerly the lieutenant governor of Maryland, serving from 2003 to 2007.

James J. L. Stegmaier has been the Chesterfield County administrator since July 2007. Before that appointment, he was the deputy county administrator for management services beginning in 1997 and the director of the county budget and management department fro 1986-97. 

Stegmaier graduated from The Catholic University of America, Washington, D.C., in 1976, and also holds a master's degree in public administration from the University of Virginia. He has also attended the Government Finance Officers Association Executive Finance Institute at Georgetown University, Leadership Metro Richmond, and the Senior Executive Institute at the University of Virginia.
Sam Stein is the political editor for the Huffington Post. He frequently appears on MSNBC. He has worked previously for Newsweek, the New York Daily News and the Center for Public Integrity.

Dan Stein is president of the Federation for American Immigration Reform, a group that "seeks to improve border security, to stop illegal immigration, and to promote immigration levels consistent with the national interest — more traditional rates of about 300,000 a year."

Rep. Jim Steineke (R-Kaukauna) was first elected to the Wisconsin State Assembly in 2010 and represents the 5th district in the Fox Cities area. He was named by his fellow Republicans as Assembly Majority Leader in the fall of 2014.
Republican Jonathan Steitz is an attorney who unsuccessfully challenged Wisconsin state Sen. Bob Wirch, D-Pleasant Prairie, in a recall election in August of 2011.
Paul Stekler, an award-winning documentary filmmaker, chairs the University of Texas Department of Radio-Television-Film.
John Stemberger is the president of the Florida Family Policy Council, a conservative Republican group that advocates against same-sex marriage and adoptions.

Mike Stenhouse is the chief executive officer of the Rhode Island Center for Freedom and Prosperity, a conservative think tank. A Cranston, R.I., native, he is a former player for the Boston Red Sox, Minnesota Twins and Montreal Expos. Previously, he was executive director of the Ocean State Policy Research Institute. He has an economics degree from Harvard University, served as chairman for the 2010 Rhode Island Clean Slate campaign, and as vice president of the Board of Directors for Rhode Island Special Olympics.

Marla Stephens is the head of the appellate division of the Wisconsin state public defender’s office. She was an unsuccessful candidate for the state Supreme Court in spring of 2011, losing in the four-way primary.
Ron Stephens, a Republican, is a member of the Georgia House of Representatives. A pharmacist, Stephens was first sworn into office in 1997 and lives in Savannah.
Stuart Sternberg is the principal owner of the Tampa Bay Rays baseball team.
District 73 representative from Sarasota. Iraq War veteran. First elected to the Florida House of Representatives in 2010.
Pat Stevens is Director of Environmental Planning for the Atlanta Regional Commission.
Sara Stevenson, a middle-school librarian in Austin, wrote an op-ed article for the Austin American-Statesman in April 2012.

Corey Stewart, a Republican, is the chairman of the Prince William County's board of supervisors. He was elected to the board in 2003 to represent the Occoquan district. Then he won a special election in 2006 to become chairman. He was elected to four-year terms in 2007 and 2011.

Stewart ran an unsuccessful campaign for the Republican nomination for lieutenant governor in 2013.

Stewart was born in Minnesota. He graduated from Georgetown University, Washington, D.C., and earned a law degree from William Mitchell College of Law, St. Paul, Minn. He works as an international trade attorney in private practice.

Pam Stewart is a former public school teacher and principal. In 2004, she was named Deputy Chancellor for Educator Quality at the Florida Department of Education. She served in that position until 2009 when she moved to the St. Johns County School District to become Deputy Superintendent for Academic Services. She returned to the department in 2011 as Chancellor of Public Schools. In August 2013, the state Board of Education named her as the interim commissioner after the resignation of Tony Bennett.

Stickland, an oil and gas consultant who represents House District 92 in the 2013 Texas Legislature, describes his philosophy as constitutional conservatism, stitching together a belief in small government, free markets, social conservatism on issues such as abortion and a streak of civil libertarianism on issues such as privacy.

Susan Stimpson, a Republican from Stafford County, was the chairwoman of the Stafford County Board of Supervisors. She was a member of the board from 2010 to 2013.

She ran for the Republican nomination for lieutenant governor in 2013. She has announced her candidacy in the House of Delegates seat in the 28th District, challenging Speaker Bill Howell in the 2015 primary election.
David Stockman served as budget director under President Ronald Reagan.

Steve Stockman, a Republican from Friendswood, returned for a second term in the U.S. House in 2013 - 16 years after his first term. He unsuccessfully sought his party's U.S. Senate nomination in 2014.
Keith Stokes, until 2012, was executive director of the Rhode Island Economic Development Corporation and a former board member of the EDC.
John Stone, former congressional aide
Jeff Stone has served as a Republican member of the Wisconsin state Assembly since 1998, representing southern Milwaukee County suburbs. He ran unsuccessfully for Milwaukee County executive in 2011.
Doug Stoner, a Democrat, served one term in the Georgia House of Representatives, from 2003-2004. He served in the Georgia Senate from 2005 to 2012.
The Stop Gillnetting Now campaign is working to qualify a citizen initiative for the November ballot in Oregon.
Ronda Storms is a state Senator for District 10 in Hillsborough, Pasco and Polk counties. She is a former member of the Hillsborough County Board of County Commissioners.
Mark Strama is a Travis County member of the Texas House. He won his first term in 2004.
State Rep. Joe Straus, R-San Antonio, was initially elected the speaker of the Texas House in 2009.
Ted Strickland was governor of Ohio from 2007 through 2010. He lost his bid for re-election in 2010 to Republican John Kasich.

Stroebel is a property developer and manager from Cedarburg who was elected to the State Assembly as a Republican in 2011 in the 60th Assembly District in southeastern Wisconsin. He was an unsuccessful candidate in the Aug. 12, 2014 primary election for Congress in the race to replace longtime U.S. Rep. Tom Petri.
Students for Concealed Carry at Florida State University believes in restoring the right to self-defense on campus to licensed, of-age citizens in the state of Florida.
Bart Stupak is a former Democratic congressman from Michigan’s 1st district. He declined to seek re-election in 2010, retiring after nine terms in office.

Scott Suder is a Republican member of the state Assembly from Abbotsford, in north central Wisconsin. He represents the 69th Assembly District and serves as the Assembly Majority leader. He was elected to the seat in 1998.
education analyst

Jim Sullivan, a Democrat, was elected to the Wisconsin state Senate in 2006 and was defeated for re-election in 2010. He represented the 5th District in the Milwaukee area. He ran unsuccessfully in the nonpartisan 2011 race for Milwaukee County executive.
Kathleen Sullivan is the town of Warren’s substance abuse coordinator. She is also program director for The BAY Team, Barrington’s Prevention Coalition.

Dan Sullivan is the Alaska Department of Public Resources commissioner. Previously, he was Alaska's attorney general. He's one of several Republicans vying to challenge Democratic Senator Mark Begich in 2014.

Sullivan helms Empower Texans, which says on its website that it exists to create and sustain a system of strong fiscal stewardship within all levels of Texas government, ensuring the greatest amounts of economic and personal liberty, and promoting public policies that provide individuals with the freedom to use their strengths and talents in pursuit of greater opportunities.
Paul Summers was attorney general in Tennessee from 1999 through 2006.
Duf Sundheim is the former chairman of the California Republican Party and a 2016 candidate for the U.S. Senate.

John E. Sununu served as a Republican U.S. senator from New Hampshire from 2003 to 2009. Before he served as a member of the U.S. House of Representatives representing New Hampshire's First Congressional District from 1997 to 2002. He lost his re-election bid for the Senate in 2008.

Sununu landed various board appointments after leaving office and became an op-ed contributor to the Boston Globe.

His father, John H. Sununu, is a former governor of New Hampshire.

Scott Surovell, D-Fairfax, was first elected to the House of Delegates in 2009. He is a Virginia native who graduated from James Madison University in 1993 and the University of Virginia law school in 1996. Surovell is a co-founding partner and owner of Surovell Isaacs Petersen & Levy PLC, an 18-attorney law firm in Fairfax
Rep. Betty Sutton is a Democrat from Ohio's 13th Congressional District.
Richard Swett is a former U.S. representative from New Hampshire.

Charlie Sykes is a radio talk show host on 620-AM (WTMJ) in Milwaukee and runs the RightWisconsin website, a political site for conservatives. The station, like the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, is owned by Journal Communications Inc.
Sherry Sylvester is communications director of Texans for Lawsuit Reform, which favors litigation limits.

Annette Taddeo-Goldstein is former chairwoman of the Miami-Dade Democratic party. She ran for lieutenant governor on a ticket with former Gov. Charlie Crist in 2014. She is running for Florida's 26th Congressional District seat, which includes parts of Miami-Dade and Monroe counties.
Victoria Taft is a conservative talk show host on KPAM radio.

Tom Tancredo is a former congressman from Colorado who ran unsuccessfully for the Republican presidential nomination in 2008. In 2010, Tancredo ran for governor of Colorado as a member of the Constitution Party and placed second to Democrat and then-Denver Mayor John Hickenlooper.
Allison Tant is the chairwoman of the Florida Democratic Party. A former lobbyist who lives in Tallahassee, she was elected to the post in January 2013.

Teresa Ann Tanzi is the Rhode Island state representative in District 34, which includes Narragansett and South Kingstown. Previously, she was a member of the South Kingstown Economic Development Committee.
Jim Taricani is a veteran Rhode Island journalist and worked as an investigative reporter at WJAR-TV in Providence until his retirement in 2014.

John Tassoni Jr., a Democratic state senator from Smithfield, R.I., was first elected to the General Assembly in 2000. He is president of The Sentinel Group, a consulting, marketing, labor relations and media relations firm in Providence. He is publisher of Common Ground, a monthly union newspaper, and previously served as a senior business agent for AFSCME Council 94.
Horacena Tate, a Democrat from Atlanta, is the Democratic Party caucus chair in the Georgia Senate.

Angel Taveras served a four-year term as the mayor of Providence, R.I. beginning in Jan. 3, 2011, the first Dominican-American to be elected mayor in the state. In 2014 he lost the Democratic primary when he ran for governor. Taveras, a lawyer and former Housing Court judge, replaced David N. Cicilline, who was elected to Congress in Rhode Island's 1st District. He is a graduate of  Harvard University and Georgetown Law School.

Taxpayer Association of Oregon was founded by Jason Williams and Don McIntire in 2000. Don McIntire is most commonly known as the father of Measure 5, the 1990 property tax limitation measure).  Jason Williams is best known for working with Oregonians In Action.
Lena Taylor is a Milwaukee Democrat, was elected to the Wisconsin Senate in 2004. She previously served for nearly two years in the state Assembly.
John Taylor, a Pawtucket, R.I., native, is chairman of the board of Twin River Management Group, which operates Twin River Casino in Lincoln, R.I.

Mary Taylor is the lieutenant governor of Ohio, elected in 2008 with Gov. John Kasich. She is the director of the Ohio Department of Insurance and also heads Kasich's “Common Sense Initiative” to reform Ohio’s regulatory policies. Prior to becoming lieutenant governor, she was a auditor of Ohio and a member of the General Assembly.

Goldie Taylor is an opinion writer and MSNBC contributor based in Atlanta, Ga. She has worked as a political consultant and journalist, and she is editor-at-large for theGrio.com, a news and opinion site geared toward African Americans. She writes about political and social issues on her online blog, The Goldie Taylor Project.
Rashad Taylor, a Democrat from Atlanta, is a member of the Georgia House of Representatives.

Catherine Taylor is a Republican who made an unsuccessful run for lieutenant governor in Rhode Island in 2014. Taylor, who also ran unsuccessfully for secretary of state in 2010, is a former speechwriter for Sens. John and Lincoln Chafee, and served as director of the Rhode Island Division of Elderly Affairs.
Rob Teilhet is a Democratic candidate for Georgia Attorney General.
State Sen. Chris Telfer is a Republican in Bend.
The Tennessee Democratic Party headquarters are in Nashville.
The Tennessee Republican Party represents Republicans in Tennessee.

Commissioner Bob Terry is the Vice-Chair of the Board and represents District 4, a large portion of the rural area of  Washington County including Banks, Cornelius, Forest Grove, Gaston, Hillsboro and North Plains. Commissioner Terry was sworn into the Washington County Board of Commissioners in January 2011. This is his first term serving as a Washington County Commissioner.

Joseph W. Testa was appointed Ohio Tax Commissioner by Gov. John Kasich in January 2011. He is the 18th tax commissioner to lead the Ohio Department of Taxation. He previously held elective offices in Franklin County, including county auditor.
Jon Tester was elected to his first term in the U.S. Senate in 2006 as a Democrat representing Montana.
Texans for Economic Development, representing horse track interests, seeks legislation asking Texas voters to legalize slot machines at tracks and several Indian reservations.
The Texas Conservatives Fund is a super PAC devoted to electing David Dewhurst to the U.S. Senate.
The Texas Democratic Party says it's "working to advance issues like job creation, comprehensive immigration reform, good schools, health care and building an economy that lasts."

The Texas Department of Transportation says its mission is to maintain existing roadways and collaborate with private and local entities to plan, design, build and maintain expanded transportation infrastructure.
The Texas House Democratic Caucus has 49 members.
Dave Nalle, a founder of the Texas Liberty PAC, told us it is a Republican-led super PAC founded in February 2014 with an initial focus on defeating two Republican House members.
The Texas Public Policy Foundation is a conservative research institute in Austin.

A statewide anti-abortion and anti-euthanasia group that celebrated its 40th anniversary in 2013, Texas Right to Life says it fights "for the rights of the unborn (including the nascent humans created in laboratories), the disabled, the sick, the elderly, and the unloved," on its website, which also states, "We are non-sectarian and non-partisan, and we are the Texas affiliate of the National Right to Life Committee with representation on their board of directors."
Kim Thatcher is the state representative for House District 25, Marion County. She is owner of KT Contracting.
The Accountability Project is a Florida Electioneering Communication Organization registered to political consultant Keith Donner. The ECO is supporting Julio Robaina for Miami Dade mayor.
The Agenda Project is a liberal advocacy group.

The Campaign to Fix the Debt, a group formed in 2012 with help from a bipartisan cast of elected officials, is a corporate-backed effort to push for action to reduce the long-term federal debt and bring down deficits. It is a vehicle created in large part by CEOs of major companies to lobby on the issue, according to media coverage in the Wall Street Journal, New York Times and Los Angeles Times.

The Commonwealth Institute provides independent research and of state fiscal and economic policies in Virginia with a focus on how they affect middle class and low income people. The Commonwealth Institute is the State Priorities Partnership (SPP) group for Virginia, part of a national network of nonpartisan, independent, nonprofit organizations in over 40 states. The SPP network is coordinated by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a Washington-based research organization and strategic policy institute that works on a range of federal and state issues.

The Family Foundation is a non-profit organization that lobbies for socially conservative policies in Virginia. Founded in 1985, the group has pushed for abortion restrictions, a constitutional amendment declaring marriage must be between a man and a woman, charter schools and conscience clauses for people peacefully exercising religious beliefs.
The Rhode Island Catholic is the official weekly newspaper of the Catholic Diocese of Providence. Formerly known as The Providence Visitor, it was renamed in 2007.

Joe Theismann played in the NFL for 12 years, winning a Super Bowl for the Washington Redskins in Super Bowl XVII. In 1983, he won the NFL's MVP award for bringing the team to another Super Bowl. The Notre Dame alumnus's pro football career ended when he broke his leg in a 1985 game.

He has worked for ESPN and the NFL Network in recent years, with occasional appearances on Fox News.
Kristi Thibaut of Houston served one term in the Texas House of Representatives after she was elected in 2008.

After 16 years as Shelby County's elected Probate Court Clerk, Thomas was elected to the County Commission in 2010. He previously served on the Memphis City Schools board before moving out of the city.
Doug Thomas is the board of directors president of the Lake Oswego Corporation.
Clarence Thomas is an associate justice on the United States Supreme Court. A Georgia native, Thomas was appointed to the court in 1991.

Alisha Thomas Morgan, a Democrat, was first elected to the Georgia House of Representatives in 2002, becoming the first African-American to be elected from a district solely in Cobb County. A graduate of Spelman College, she is running for Georgia's school superintendent.
Hugh Thompson, a native Georgian, was appointed to the Supreme Court of Georgia in 1994. Thompson served as a superior court judge in the eight-county Ocmulgee Judicial Circuit from 1979 to 1994.
U.S. Representative Mike Thompson is a Democrat and represents the Napa and Sonoma counties region in Northern California.

Fred Thompson was a U.S. senator from Tennessee from 1994 to 2003. He graduated from Memphis State University and earned a law degree at Vanderbilt University. Thompson practiced law and served a variety of government counsel positions, including as minority counsel for the Senate Select Committee on Presidential Campaign Activities ("Watergate Committee"). In his acting career Thompson has appeared in 18 films, and recently worked as a TV actor, playing a prosecutor on the series  Law and Order.  Thompson was born in Alabama in 1942. He has been married to Jeri Kehn since 2002, and has four children, two from his first marriage. He withdrew from the presidential race on Jan. 22, 2008.

Tommy Thompson, a Republican, was a 2012 candidate for the U.S. Senate from Wisconsin. He served as governor of Wisconsin from 1987 until 2001, when he left office to become President George W. Bush's secretary of health and human services. He previously spent 20 years in the Wisconsin Assembly. Thompson briefly ran for president, withdrawing in 2007.

A Houston lawyer first elected to the state House of Representatives in 1973, Thompson "has served longer in the Legislature than any other woman or African-American in Texas history," according to her House biography, and chairs the House Local and Consent Calendars Committee.
State Rep. Geraldine Thompson is an Orlando Democrat representing District 39. She was first elected in 2006.
Maurice A. Thompson is executive director of 1851 Center for Constitutional Law, a law firm dedicated to protecting the constitutional rights of Ohioans from government abuse.
John Thrasher is a Republican state Senator representing District 8 in Northeast Florida and the chairman of the Republican Party of Florida.
John Thune is a U.S. Senator who represents South Dakota.
Todd Tiahrt is a former U.S. representative from Kansas. He sought the Republican U.S. Senate nomination to succeed Sam Brownback in 2010, but lost to fellow Rep. Jerry Moran.

Bob Tiernan was elected as chairman of the Oregon Republican Party in January 2009. He served in the Oregon House from 193 to 1997. He was sponsor of three Oregon ballot measures: Measure 11, mandatory sentences; Measure 8, pension reform; and Measure 17, prison work.

	He is president of  Tiernan and Associates and owner of  the new PayLess Drug.

	Tiernan has a bachelor's degree from Oregon State University, a law degree from Seattle University School of Law and an  LLM from Georgetown University Law School.
Thom Tillis is a Republican who serves as House Speaker in North Carolina. He is running for the U.S. Senate seat occupied by Democrat Kay Hagan.
PAC formed to help Michelle Nunn's U.S. Senate bid.
Lisa P. Tomasso is a Democratic state representative for District 29 -- Coventry, West Greenwich. She was elected to the General Assembly in 2010.

Richard Tomlins ran an unsuccessful campaign for mayor in Cranston, R.I. in 2010. He was a business manager for Boston University and Barnard College in New York before moving to the hotel business and retiring as a general manager of Sheraton's subsidiaries.

Tomorrow's Vision of Florida is an electioneering communication organization formed by former state legislator Edward Bullard and state Sen. Larcenia Bullard. Their son, Democratic state Rep. Dwight Bullard of Miami, is running in a state senate primary against Democratic leader and state Rep. Ron Saunders.
Jeffrey Toobin is a staff writer for the New Yorker, a legal analyst for CNN and an author of several books about the law.

Pat Toomey is a U.S. senator from Pennsylvania, having won election to his seat in 2010 by defeating Democratic Rep. Joe Sestak. Toomey occupies the seat formerly held by Sen. Arlen Specter, to whom he narrowly lost in the 2004 Republican U.S. Senate primary.
Represented Corpus Christi's District 33 in the state House 2011-13; owner since 1993 of accounting/financial services firm.

David Toscano, D-57th, is the minority leader of the Virginia House of Delegates. The district includes Charlottesville and part of Albemarle county. He was elected to the house in 2005 and became minority leader in 2011. He sits on the Transportation, Courts of Justice and Science and Technology committees.

He previously served on the Charlottesville City Council from 1990 to 2002 and was mayor in 1994-96.

Toscano was born in Syracuse, N.Y. Toscano received a bachelor’s degree from Colgate University, Hamilton, N.Y., in 1972, a doctorate in sociology from Boston College in 1979, and a law degree from the University of Virginia in 1986. His law practice in Charlottesville specializes in family matters. He has taught political science and sociology at several universities.

Kathie Tovo, who initially won election to the Austin City Council in 2011, won election to the District 9 single-member council district in 2014. Tovo is a former member of the city planning commission and former vice president of the Austin Neighborhoods Council, her campaign biography says.
The Traditional Values Coalition is a religious activist group with conservative values based in Washington, D.C.

Jack Trammell, the Democratic Party candidate for the 7th Congressional District in 2014, is an assistant professor of sociology and director of disability support services at Randolph-Macon College, Ashland. He graduated from Grove City College, Grove City, Pa., and a master's and doctorate degree at Virginia Commonwealth University, along with a special education certification program at the University of Virginia. 

Trammell has been an educator at the K-12 or university level for more than 20 years. He also writes nonfiction, fiction and children's books. He lives on a farm in Louisa County wiht his wife Audrie, a special education teacher and artist. He has seven children.

Joshua Treviño, formerly of the Texas Public Poilcy Foundation, based in Austin, says in an online biographical entry that he was previously the founder and president of Treviño Strategies and Media, where he worked on national and international media campaigns. His entry also says his experience encompasses work in more than 30 countries.

Joseph A. Trillo, a Republican representing District 24 in Warwick, has served in the House since 2001. He is the House Minority Whip, a member of the Corporations Committee, and President of AAA Custom Alarms/Real Estate Investing.
Ellen Troxclair, elected in 2014 to represent a Southwest Austin district on the Austin City Council, says she otherwise volunteers in the community and manages a real estate management business.
Rep. Carlos Trujillo is a Miami attorney first elected to the Florida House in 2010.

Dr. Nick Tsiongas, a physician, is a former Rhode Isalnd state legislator and past president of the Rhode Island Medical Society. He also is a founding board member of HealthRIght, a Rhode Island group working for “the passage and implementation of comprehensive health care reform."
Rob Turner is the Hillsborough County Property Appraiser.
Michael Turner, a former mayor of Dayton, is a member of the House of Representatives from Ohio's 3rd District in the southwestern corner of the state.
Shirley Turner is a Democratic state senator representing parts of Hunterdon and Mercer counties.
Scott Turner, a former NFL player, won election to the Texas House in 2012. He declared his candidacy for Texas House speaker in January 2014.

Nina Turner is a state senator from the 25th Senate District in Cleveland. She joined the Ohio Senate in September 2008 after serving on Cleveland City Council. She also served in the administration of former Cleveland Mayor Michael White. In addition to her duties in the Ohio Senate, she teaches at Cuyahoga Community College.
George Turner has been Atlanta's Chief of Police since 2010.
Sylvester Turner, of Houston, was first elected to the Texas House in 1988.
Holly Turner is a lawyer who grew up in Seguin and moved to the district from Fort Worth in July 2009.
Jeff Turner, a Democrat, is the chairman of the Clayton County Board of Commissioners. Turner was the county's former police chief.
Eric Turner, a former Indiana state legislator, is director of governmental affairs for American Promotional Events.
Michael W. Tyler is Chariman of the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority's Board of Directors.

Laura Tyson chaired the Council of Economic Advisers and the National Economic Council under President Bill Clinton. She is currently a professor at the Haas School of Business at the University of California (Berkeley).
Uber is a ride-sharing service with providers in many cities including Austin.

Stephen R. Ucci is the deputy majority leader of the state House of Representatives. First elected in 2004, Ucci represents Johnston and Cranston. He is a lawyer for Raytheon and a resident of Johnston.

Mark Emery Udall is the senior United States Senator from Colorado and a member of the Democratic Party. From 1999 to 2009, Udall served in the United States House of Representatives, representing Colorado's 2nd congressional district
UltraViolet describes itself as "a community of women and men, fighting to expand women's rights and combat sexism everywhere - from politics and government to media and pop culture."
Bryan Underwood owns and operates a contracting business in Seguin.

United Florida Horsemen is an advocacy group comprised of the Florida Quarter Horse Racing Association, the Florida Horsemen's Benevolent & Protective Association, Florida Thoroughbred Breeders' and Owners' Association, and the Florida Quarter Horse Breeders' and Owners' Association.
United for a Fair Economy is a group that “raises awareness that concentrated wealth and power undermine the economy."
Renee Unterman, a Republican, is a Georgia state senator who represents portions of Gwinnett County.
Fred Upton is a Republican U.S. Representative from Michigan. He is chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee.
Hector Uribe, a former state senator, sought the 2010 Democratic nod for Texas land commissioner. Uribe is an Austin lawyer and lobbyist.
Valerie Vainieri Huttle is a Democratic state Assemblywoman representing Bergen County.
Larry Valencia, a Democrat, is a member of the Rhode Island House of Representatives, representing portions of Richmond, Exeter and Hopkinton. He is a freelance medical and technical writer.
Sher Valenzuela,  a small business owner and professional writer, is the Republican nominee for lieutenant governor of Delaware in 2012.
Paul Valletta Jr. is a firefighter and a lobbyist for the Rhode Island State Association of Firefighters.
J.D. Van Brink, chairman of the Georgia Tea Party
Philip Van Cleave is president of the Virginia Citizens Defense League, a pro-gun lobbying group in Virginia that was founded in 1994..
Chris Van Hollen is a Democratic U.S. Congressman from Maryland.

J.B. Van Hollen, a Republican, was elected Wisconsin attorney general in 2006. He is a former U.S. attorney for Wisconsin's Western District and previously served as district attorney in both Ashland and Bayfield counties.
Rep. Charles Van Zant is a Republican representing District 19. He is an architect from Keystone Heights who was first elected to the House in 2008.
Leticia Van de Putte, a pharmacist, was the 2014 Democratic nominee for lieutenant governor. She previously served in the Texas House.
Jesse Ventura is an author, a former governor of Minnesota (1999-2003) and a former professional wrestler.
Jason Villalba, a lawyer, won his first term in the Texas House in 2012.
Mike Villarreal, a House member since 2000, resigned his seat on the cusp of the 2015 legislative session to run for mayor of San Antonio.
James Vincent is president of the Providence branch of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP).

The Virginia Center for Public Safety is a non-profit, non-partisan grass roots organization dedicated to the reduction of gun violence in Virginia. VACPS strives to accomplish this mission through awareness, education and advocacy of gun restrictions.
Democrats elected to serve in the State Senate.
The Virginia Society for Human Life, founded in 1967, is a non-sectarian public education group that opposes abortion and believes life begins at the moment of fertilization.

Jill Holtzman-Vogel, R-Fauquier, was first elected to the Senate of Virginia in 2008. She is managing partner of a law firm that specializes in charity and non-profit organizations, election law and ethics. She prviously worked as a deputy general counsel at the U.S. Department of Energy.

Vogel is a graduate of the College of William & Mary and DePaul University School of Law.

George Voinovich, a Republican, was a U.S. Senator from Ohio. He retired at the end of his term in 2010. Prior to that he was governor of Ohio, mayor of Cleveland and served in the Ohio General Assembly.

Wisconsin state Rep. Robin Vos, R-Rochester, has represented western Racine County in the state Assembly since 2004. In November 2012, he was elected Assembly speaker. Vos previously served on the Racine County Board of Supervisors, from 1994 to 2004.
The Vote NO on 8 group is urging Florida residents to vote against Amendment 8, the class size amendment.

Voters First Ohio supports an amendment to the Ohio Constitution that would overhaul the way boundaries are drawn for congressional and legislative districts. It is led by the League of Women Voters and supported by a broad coalition of groups and people.
Republican Leah Vukmir was elected to the Wisconsin state Senate in 2010, representing a suburban Milwaukee district. She served in the state Assembly from 2002 to 2008.
The Waco Tea Party advocates for limited government, free markets and fiscal responsibility.
Greg Walden is a U.S. representative from Oregon. He is leading the transition as Republicans take power in the 112th Congress.
State Rep. James "Jim" Waldman, D-Coconut Creek, was first elected to the Legislature in 2006 and is the former mayor of  Coconut Creek.

Patrick Wales is project manager for Virginia Uranium Inc., which wants to mine uranium at Coles Hill in Pittsylvania County. Wales was born in Charlottesville and raised in Danville, and he now lives in Danville with his wife, an elementary school teacher, and 3-year-old son. He holds a bachelor’s degree in geology from Radford University and a master’s in geology from the University of Mississippi. He has been with Virginia Uranium since 2007.

Scott Walker, a Republican, was elected governor of Wisconsin in November 2010. He was recalled in 2012 after igniting controversy with a bill curtailing public-employee union collective-bargaining rights. He survived the recall election, defeating Milwaukee Mayor Tom Barrett.  He won re-election to a four-year term in November 2014 and was a 2016 presidential candidate before dropping out in September of 2015. Walker is a former Milwaukee County executive and former member of the state Assembly.

Erik Wallin is a Republican who made an unsuccessful run for Attorney General in 2010. He graduated from Rhode Island College and Roger Williams Law School. He served as a military lawyer in a variety of capacities before returning to Rhode Island where he worked as an assistant attorney general for five years, until 2008, when he left to open his own law office in South Kingstown.
Joe Walsh is a member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Illinois.
Robert A. Walsh Jr. is executive director of the National Education Association of Rhode Island (NEARI), which represents 11,800 educators and support staff.
Dr. Michele Walsh is division chief of neonatology at Rainbow Babies & Children's Hospital in Cleveland.
Weston Wamp in 2012 is running for Tennessee's 3rd Congressional District seat that his father, Zach Wamp, held until after his unsuccessful run for Tennessee governor in 2010.

Alex Wan is the District 6 member of the Atlanta City Council, which includes intown neighborhoods like Midtown, Morningside and Virginia-Highland. He is the director of Development for Jerusalem House, Atlanta's oldest and largest provider of permanent, supportive housing for homeless or low-income individuals and families living with HIV/AIDS.
Matt Wand was elected to the Troutdale City Council in 2008. He is an attorney with the firm he founded, Wand Law Firm, Gresham.
former Georgia Chief Justice

Mark Warner, a Democrat, has represented Virginia in the U.S. Senate since 2009. He serves on the Banking, Budget, Commerce and Intelligence committees. He is the honorary co-chairman of the Forward Together PAC.

Warner gave the keynote address at the 2008 Democratic National Convention. Warner previously served as governor of Virginia from 2002 to 2006. He also ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in 1996. Before public office, Warner was an early investor in the cell phone business, co-founded the company that became Nextel.

Warner was born in Indianapolis, Ind., and grew up in Illinois and Connecticut. Warner graduated from George Washington University, Washington, D.C. He received a law degree from Harvard Law School, Cambridge, Mass.
The Rev. Raphael Warnock is the senior pastor of Ebenezer Baptist Church, located in Atlanta. The church's former pastors include the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.

Elizabeth Warren is a U.S. Senator from Massachusetts. A former Harvard law professor, she ran against Sen. Scott Brown, R-Mass. in 2012. In 2008, she headed an oversight panel for Congress' Troubled Asset Relief Program, better known by its acronym, TARP. Warren helped create the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, which she oversaw as an interim director. Born in Oklahoma City in 1949, Warren moved to Massachusetts in 1995 with her husband Bruce Mann, also a Harvard law professor. She has a daughter, Amelia, and a son, Alex.

Debbie Wasserman Schultz is chairwoman of the Democratic National Committee and a Florida Democrat elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in 2004. She represents Congressional District 23 in Broward and Miami-Dade counties.
John Watson is a senior adviser to Citizens for Transportation Mobility, an organization supporting Georgia's transportation sales tax referendum.

Kirk Watson, who initially won his seat in the Texas Senate in 2006, was previously mayor of Austin. Earlier, he served on the Texas Air Control Board, precursor to the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality. He was the 2002 Democratic nominee for Texas attorney general.
Stan Watson, a Democrat, is the District 7 representative on the DeKalb County Board of Commissioners. Watson is a former member of the Georgia House of Representatives.
Robert Watson, a Republican from East Greenwich, was House Minority Leader from 1998 to 2011. He retired at the end of the 2012 session.
Accordng to his campaign biography, Watts is a businessman, author and minister who lives between Gilmer and Longview in East Texas.

We Are Ohio is a citizen-driven, community-based, bipartisan coalition that has come together to repeal Senate Bill 5 in Ohio. The legislation would overhaul rules for collective bargaining by public employees.

We Are Wisconsin formed in summer 2011 for the state senate recall elections. It is a group composed of labor unions. We Are Wisconsin formed a political action committee and funded campaign advertising and other activities.

The White House has created a page on its website that allows citizens to post petitions. The page, called We the People, Your Voice in Our Government, allows citizens to present issues directly to the government. If a petition gets 25,000 online signatures in a month, it may get an official response from the White House.
State Rep. Will Weatherford, R-Wesley Chapel, is Florida's Speaker of the House for 2013-14.

Jim Webb is running for president of the United States in 2016.

Webb, a Democrat, served as a U.S. senator from Virginia in 2007-13. He served as the first Assistant Secreatry of Defense for Reserve Affairs and Secretary of the Navy in the Ronald Reagan administration.

Webb is a 1968 graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy and served as a Marine Corps infantry officer until 1972 and saw action in the Vietnam War, for which he was awarded the Navy Cross, Silver Star, two Bronze Stars and two Purple Hearts.

Webb was born in Saint Joseph, Mo. He also has a law degree from Georgetown Law Center, Washington, D.C. He has written fiction and nonfictions books and won an Emmy award for his 1983 PBS coverage of the U.S. Marines in Beirut. He frequently writes opinion columns for many publications.
Jay Webber is a Republican state Assemblyman representing parts of Essex, Morris and Passaic counties. Webber previously served as chairman of the state Republican Party.
Daniel Webster, a former Florida House Speaker and Senate Majority Leader, is a Republican representing Congressional District 8 in Central Florida.

Jeff Weems was the Democratic party's 2010 nominee for a seat on the Texas Railroad Commission. He practices law in Houston representing operating companies, energy service companies, royalty and land owners, according to his campaign website.

Dr. Wehby has practiced for 15 years and has held numerous leadership positions at the local, state and national levels. She currently is the director of pediatric neurosurgery at Randall Children's Hospital in Portland.
Jim Weidner worked in mills in vibration analysis and owns the restaurant, Lago de Chapala. He was elected to the Oregon House in 2008.
Bill Weimer is the vice president of Youngstown, Ohio,-based Phantom Fireworks, the nation's largest retailer of consumer fireworks.
Anthony Weiner is a Congressman who represents parts of New York City, including Brooklyn, Kew Gardens and Rockaway.
Dave Weldon is a former member of the U.S. House of Representatives who is running for the U.S. Senate.
Jeff Wentworth, a state senator from San Antonio, lost his bid for the 2012 Republican nomination for the seat.
Allen West, a retired U.S. Army Colonel, was elected to the U.S. House on Nov. 2, 2010. He took office Jan. 5, 2011 and served one term. He now is a contributor for Fox News.

Bing West is a Marine veteran of the Vietnam War and a former assistant secretary of defense for international security affairs in the Reagan administration. He is the author of numerous books on military affairs.

The former public defender for Shelby County has won landslide victories since first running for mayor of Shelby County in 2002, taking two county mayoral elections before winning a special election in 2009 to become Memphis's first new mayor in 18 years, succeeding Willie Herenton. Wharton won another landslide in 2011 and his first full four-year term began on Jan. 1, 2012.

	Wharton received his law degree in 1971, graduating with honors from the University of Mississippi Law School, where he was one of the first African-American students to serve on the Moot Court Board and first to serve on the Judicial Council. He became the University's first African-American professor of law, where he taught for 25 years. He earned a political science degree from Tennessee State University and is a native of Lebanon, Tennessee.

	The Mayor and his wife, Ruby, have raised six sons in Memphis.

John Whitbeck was elected chairman of the Republican Party of Virginia in 2015. He has a family law practice in Leesburg, Va.

A California native, Whitbeck got an A.B. degree in politics from Occidental College. He graduated from George Mason University's law school.
Bill White, an author, is a San Antonio native who was mayor of Houston from 2004-2009. He was the 2010 Democratic nominee for governor of Texas.
Molly White, a conservative activist, represents a Belton-based district in the Texas House.
Sheldon Whitehouse is a Democratic U.S. Senator from Rhode Island.

Christine Todd Whitman was New Jersey's 50th governor, serving from 1994 to 2001. She left the governor's office to become administrator of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency under then President George W. Bush. Today she is president of The Whitman Strategy Group.

Meg Whitman is the former CEO of eBay and the 2010 Republican gubernatorial nominee in California. Largely self-financing her campaign, Whitman lost the general election to then-Attorney General Jerry Brown.
John Whitmire is a Houston attorney who was first elected to the Texas Senate in 1982. Prior, he served in the Texas House of Representatives.
Republican Lenar Whitney is a Louisiana state representative running for U.S. Congress in 2014 in District 6, an open seat that represents parts of Baton Rouge.

Sen. Doug Whitsett, a former veterinarian, owns two small farms in the Klamath Basin, which breed and raise European Warmblood Horses for dressage and jumping. He is past president of the Oregon Veterinary Medical Association. He represents Senate District 28, Klamath Falls.
Chris Widener represents Ohio's the 10th Senate District, which includes Madison, Clark and Greene counties. He previously he served three terms in the Ohio House of Representatives.

Todd Wilcox is an Orlando businessman running for U.S. Senate. He is a former Special Forces commander and combat veteran who worked for the CIA before opening his defense contracting company, Patriot Defense Group.
Jay Wiley was a 2014 candidate for the the District 6 seat on the Austin City Council.
Joe Wilkinson, a Republican, is chairman of the House Ethics Committee
George Will is a conservative columnist syndicated by the Washington Post.
Ash Williams is executive director and chief investment officer of the State Board of Administration
Nikema Williams is the interim chairwoman of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
Sandra Williams is a member of the Ohio House of Representatives. She was first elected in 2006. She represents the 11th District, which encompasses part of Cleveland.

Roger Williams won election to represent the newly created Congressional District 25 in 2012. He is a former Texas secretary of state, the state's chief elections officer. He was appointed by President George W. Bush in 2001 as chairman of the Republican National Finance Committee’s Eagles fundraising program and also has served as state finance chair for John Cornyn's 2002 Senate campaign, according to his campaign website.
Anastasia P. Williams is a state representative in Rhode Island, representing District 9 in Providence.

Michael Williams is a former member of the Texas Railroad Commission. He lost his 2012 bid to be the Republican nominee for a U.S. House seat. He was later appointed the state's education commissioner.
Kyle Williams, a Democrat, is an attorney based in Decatur and involved in several community organizations.
Hank Williams Jr. is a renowned, rowdy country singer. He is the sole son of the late legend, Hank Williams.

Kevin D. Williamson is National Review’s roving correspondent. His Exchequer blog covers debt, deficits, and the intersection of finance and politics. He is the author of "The End Is Near and It’s Going To Be Awesome: How Going Broke Will Leave America Richer, Happier, and More Secure" among other books.
Jennifer Williamson is running in the Democratic primary to represent Oregon House District 36.

Brian Wilson has a long history of community service, though no elected experience. Most notably, he led the Multnomah County Library’s successful 2012 campaign to get win voter approval for a library district.
Joe Wilson is a Republican Congressman from South Carolina. He represents the 2nd district, which include Columbia, Beaufort and Hilton Head Island.

Valarie Wilson, a Democrat, is a candidate for Georgia school superintendent. Wilson is a former chairwoman of the Decatur school board, former president of Georgia School Boards Association, served on Governor Nathan Deal’s Education Advisory Board and was a member of the Decatur Education Foundation.
Frederica Wilson, a former Florida state senator from Miami Gardens, was elected to the U.S. House on Nov. 2, 2010. She represents Congressional District 24 in South Florida.
Matt Wingard represents Oregon House District 26. He was first elected in 2008. He runs a public relations consulting firm in Wilsonville.

Wisconsin state Sen. Bob Wirch, a Democrat from Pleasant Prairie in Kenosha County in southeastern Wisconsin, has served in the Senate since 1996. He survived a recall election in 2011. Wirch served in the state Assembly from 1992 to 1996.

The Wisconsin Association for Justice, formerly the Wisconsin Academy of Trial Lawyers, says its mission is to "promote a fair and effective justice system - one that ensures justice for all, not just a privileged few.  The Association supports the work of attorneys to ensure any person harmed due to work place injury or injured by the misconduct or negligence of others can have a fair day in court, even when taking on the most powerful interests."
Wisconsin Contractor Coalition is comprised of 400 firms in the construction contracting business that was formed in late 2014 to opposed enactment of a so-called "Right to Work" law in Wisconsin.
The Wisconsin Corn Growers Association is an industry group active in promoting corn and related products.
WEAC, the Wisconsin Education Association Council, is the state's largest teachers union. It also represents education support staff and some university employees.
Wisconsin Family Action is an arm of the Wisconsin Family Council. It advocates against same sex marriage and “foundational issues such as marriage, life and liberty.”

The 130-year-old Wisconsin Humane Society is one of the largest and oldest humane societies in the country. The mission of the Wisconsin Humane Society is to build a community where people value animals and treat them with respect and kindness.

The Wisconsin Institute for Law & Liberty is a conservative, libertarian public interest law firm, based in Milwaukee, that initiates legal actions on a range of public issues.

	Rick Esenberg was named president and general council of the 501(c)(3) organization, which gets financial backing from the Milwaukee-based Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation.

	As the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported: "The institute has entered the fray on a range of cases, from Act 10, the legislation that curtailed collective bargaining in Wisconsin for most public sector workers, to voter identification to the proposed Milwaukee streetcar project. In each case, the institute took the conservative side on the issue."

Wisconsin Manufacturers and Commerce is Wisconsin's largest business group. It says its members include large and small manufacturers, service companies, local chambers of commerce and specialized trade associations. WMC is also a lobbying organization and often gets involved in state political races.
The Wisconsin Medical Society is a trade group for the state's physicians. It has more than 12,000 members.

The Wisconsin Professional Police Association is the largest law enforcement labor union in the state, representing local police, sheriff’s deputies and other officers. It serves almost 11,000 active and retired members in 380 locals. It does not represent Milwaukee police officers, who are covered by a separate union. The WPPA engages in collective bargaining and legislative lobbying.

According to the Wisconsin Democracy Campaign, the Sierra Club is a pro-environment membership organization with a major focus on lobbying. It has been making independent expenditures since the 1996 election cycle and helped pioneer the use of "issue" ads. The group supported Democratic Party candidates in the 2011 Wisconsin Senate recall elections.
The Wisconsin Transportation Builders Association is a trade group representing roadbuilding firms and others in the transportation construction industry. It is active in lobbying and education.
Four Democratic state senators in Wisconsin were targeted by Wisconsin Manufacturers and Commerce with TV ads in the 2010 election.
Stephen Wise is a Republican state senator from the 5th District of Florida. He was elected to the state Senate in 2001. Prior to that, he was a member of the Florida House of Representatives.
John Wisniewski is a Democratic state Assemblyman representing a part of Middlesex County. Wisniewski also is chairman of the state Democratic Party.

Rob Wittman, a Republican, represents Virginia's first 1st Congressional District, which stretches from Newport News to some outlying Norther Virginia preincts.

Wittman worked for 20 years at the Virginia Department of Health as an environmental health specialist and as field director for the Division of Shellfish Sanitation.

He served on the Montross Town Council from 1986 to 1996 and on the Westmoreland County Board of Supervisors from 1996 to 2005. He was elected to the Virginia House of Delegates in 2005. Two years later, he won a special election to Congress following the death of Rep. Jo Ann Davis, a Republican.

Wittman holds a B.S. in biology from Virginia Tech, a Master's degree in public health from the University of North Carolina and a Ph.D. in public policy and administration from Virginia Commonwealth University.

Frank Wolf, R-10th, has been a member of the U.S. House of Representatives since 1981. The 10th District stretches from McLean to Winchester. Wolf sits on the House Appropriations Committee, where he is the Chairman of the Commerce, Justice and Science subcommittee. In addition, he is the co-chairman of the Tom Lantos Human Rights Commission, a bipartisan organization made up of more than 200 members of Congress who work together to raise awareness about international human rights issues. Wolf announced in December 2013 that he would not run for re-election in 2014.

Wolf served as a lawyer in the U.S. Army Reserves. He lost the first two congressional elections he ran in before winning in 1980.

Wolf was born in 1939 in Philadelphia. He received his undergraduate degree from Penn State University in 1961 and his law degree from Georgetown University in 1965.
Tom Wolf is a Democrat running for the gubernatorial nomination in Pennsylvania in 2014. Wolf, a businessman, served as state revenue secretary in 2007 and 2008 under Democratic Gov. Ed Rendell.
Nelson Wolff, a former San Antonio member of the Texas House and Senate, also served on the San Antonio City Council before becoming mayor. In 2010, he won another term as Bexar County judge.

Karina Holyoak Wood is a policy director for the American Lung Association and director of Tobacco Free Rhode Island, a statewide network of more than 55 organizations.

Richard Woods was elected January 2015 as state superintendent. He's a republican.

Paul Workman is the founder of Workman Commercial Construction and director of development for T. Stacy & Associates. He was initially elected to the Texas House in 2010.
Ritch Workman is a Republican member of the Florida House of Representatives representing Disctrict 30 in the Melbourne area. He is a mortgage broker.

Ridesharing Works for Austin raised the signatures needed to place Proposition 1 on Austin's May 7, 2016 ballot. If approved, the proposition would require the city to accept name-based background checks of drivers for ride-hailing services conducted by the services. If rejected, such drivers would be required to undergo fingerprinting and national background checks run through the FBI.
Robin Wright is a veteran diplomatic correspondent who is currently a senior fellow at the U.S. Institute of Peace.
Kyleen Wright, the mother of four boys, says that she is a past president of Greater Tarrant Right to Life. She calls the Texans for Life Coalition the largest pro-life group in the state.

Dean Wright of Austin is founder and president of New Revolution Now, which describes itself as a party-agnostic organization created to harness  the "core conservative values of mainstream  Americans to elect the state and U.S. congressional representatives who will return  the country to its founding values of limited government, low taxation, states rights and constitutional constructionism."
WrongWayRubio.com is a website that opposes Sen. Marco Rubio, R-Fla. It is a joint project of Progress Florida and Florida Watch.

David Wu, the first Chinese-American to serve in the House of Representatives, has represented Oregon’s First Congressional District since 1999.  He earned a bachelor of science from Stanford University in 1977 and a law degree from Yale University in 1982. He is co-founder of the firm Cohen and Wu.

Samuel J. Wurzelbacher gained national fame as “Joe the Plumber” during the 2008 presidential election. He is the Republican nominee for Ohio's newly drawn 9th Congressional District in the 2012 election. His Democratic opponent is longtime Democratic incumbent Marcy Kaptur.
Ron Wyden is the Democratic U.S. Senator from Oregon.

Will Wynn, a former Austin mayor, says on his website that he consults with and advises various governments, utilities and private entities on issues related to energy policy, downtown revitalization, public health and the creative class.
J. Xavier is a hip hop artist from Houston.

Kendra Yarbrough Camarena was the 2010 Democratic nominee for the House seat held by Dwayne Bohac, a Republican. According to her campaign website, she's a teacher, mother of two and also helps her husband coach Little League teams.
John Yarmuth is a Democratic member of the House of Representatives from Kentucky.

The Oregon campaign, backed in large part by the Oregon Association of Realtors, behind Ballot Measure 79. The group was known as Protect Oregon Homes when lobbying for a constitutional ban on real estate transfer taxes. The measure is on the November 2012 ballot.
"Yes on 8 Florida" is a group urging residents to vote in favor of Amendment 8, which would change a 2002 amendment about class sizes.
Ted Yoho has represented Florida's 3rd district in the U.S. House of Representatives since his election in 2012. He has practiced as a veterinarian.

Susan Yoshihara, of Portsmouth, R.I., is the director of research at the Catholic Family and Human Rights Institute, an organization with offices in Washington D.C. and New York. She received a Ph.D. in international relations from the Fletcher School, Tufts University and spent 20 years as a U.S. Navy helicopter pilot.
Del. Joseph Yost, R-Montgomery, was elected to the General Assembly in 2012.
David Yost, a Republican, was elected Ohio auditor in 2010. He previously was a county prosecutor from Delaware County in Ohio.

U.S. Rep. C. W. Bill Young, R-Indian Shores, represented the 13th Congressional District of Florida. He was the nation's longest-serving Republican congressman on the day of his death, Oct. 18, 2013. Young held public office for more than 50 years, including a decade in the Florida Senate and 22 terms in Congress.

Young was born in Harmarville, Penn., on Dec. 16, 1930. His family moved to Pinellas County when he was 15. He is a veteran of the Army National Guard. He married his second wife, Beverly, in 1985. They have two sons, Billy and Patrick, and Robbie from her first marriage.
Don Young, a Republican, holds Alaska's lone seat in the U.S. House of Representatives. He was originally elected in 1972.
Todd Young is a Republican U.S. representative from Indiana. The former attorney defeated incumbent Democrat Baron Hill in 2010 for the state’s 9th district seat.
The Young Conservatives of Texas describes itself as a non-partisan conservative youth organization.
Your Choice Colorado is a campaign pushing a Colorado ballot measure to allow full-strength beer and wine in grocery and big box stores.
Eugene Yu is a Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate in Georgia.

Mark Zaccaria is a Rhode Island Republican who ran unsuccessfully for one of the state's U.S. Senate seats in 2014. He also made two unsuccessful bids for Rhode Island's 2nd Congressional District, the most recent in 2010. He is a former chairman of the Rhode Island Republican Party. Born in 1949, he is a former corporate executive who operates a business-to-business marketing consulting business. A former Air Force instructor pilot, he served two terms on the North Kingstown Town Council and four years on the local zoning board. He is married with three children.
Judith Zaffirini, initially elected to the Texas Senate in 1986, represents a district stretching from Laredo toward Austin.
Current Allegheny County district attorney is running for attorney general of Pennsylvania.

Jim Zehringer, a Republican, is a former state representative from Fort Recovery. A former farmer, he was appointed by Gov. John Kasich to be Ohio's agriculture director.

Roy Zimmerman is a singer-songwriter who often writes about political issues, mostly satirizing conservatives and Republicans. His YouTube channel has nearly 20,000 subscribers.
Don Zimmerman, who ran for the Texas House in 2006, won election to the Austin City Council in 2014. He represents District 6 on the council.

Rich Zipperer, a Republican, is a member of the Wisconsin state Senate, representing a district covering Milwaukee's western suburbs. He was elected to the post in 2010, after two terms in the state Assembly.
